<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Envoy of Pakistani PM Arrives in Nepal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz
Sharif's special envoy Akram Zaki arrived here Saturday on a
mission to brief Nepali leaders about Pakistan's perception of the
current situation in South Asia after the nuclear tests conducted
by India and Pakistan in May.
</P>
<P>
Talking to Xinhua at the airport, Zaki said one of the purposes
of his visit is to exchange views and prepare the ground for the
10th summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) to be held late this month in Colombo, Sri
Lanka.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his current tour of Nepal, Bangladesh, Sri
Lanka and the Maldives, he would hold talks with leaders of the
four countries on how the summit can be helpful in reducing
tension and stabilizing the security situation in South Asia.
</P>
<P>
He said he was carrying letters from Prime Minister Sharif to
the leaders of the four countries.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Canada and the United States last month,
Zaki also explained the new development in South Asia to
legislators of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"Although we wanted our region to be a nuclear-free zone, we
were pushed into the situation in self-defense," he said. "But it
is very important that serious negotiations take place to resolve
the issue, specially the Kashmir question."
</P>
<P>
He said his country wants the whole world to mediate in the
dispute of Kashmir, because it has lingered on for too long a
time.
</P>
<P>
"It must be solved and it is only by solving the dispute of
Kashmir that we can have a stable and peaceful South Asia where we
can work for progress, and we are ready and much interested in
developing the SAARC region," he added.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the South Asia region is left behind in the world
and has more poor people than any other area.
</P>
<P>
He said both the United States and Canada have realized that
the Kashmir dispute has been pending for too long and must be
solved.
</P>
<P>
India and Pakistan have fought three wars since their
independence in 1947 and two of them were over Kashmir.
</P>
<P>
India has ruled out any outside mediation in its dispute with
Pakistan, including that of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Zaki is scheduled to leave for Bangladesh on July 8. 
</P>
</TEXT>
