<HEADLINE> Pakistan Says Determined to Eliminate Child labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Minister of State for Women
Development and Social Welfare Tehmina Daultana said Saturday that
there is a strong political will at the top level of Pakistan to
eliminate child labor in the country.
</P>
<P>
"We want our children in schools and not in workshops or
industries," she said.
</P>
<P>
The government is making efforts to provide education to every
child so that the new generation could become educated and
responsible citizens of the country, she told a workshop.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, organized by the National Commission for Child
Welfare and Development (NCCWD), is designed to develop a draft
plan of action for elimination of child labor and protection of
working children.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the government has not only supported
broad-based social development strategies but has also taken
initiatives for eliminating child labor.
</P>
<P>
It is the moral responsibility of all citizens of the country
to work together and cooperate with the government to solve the
problem, she said.
</P>
<P>
She also called for launching a mass awareness campaign about
child labor and said a non-formal basic education program should
be introduced for education of dropped-out children from schools.
</P>
<P>
Tehmina said Pakistan has ratified the Convention of Right of
Child (CRC) in 1990 and is committed to including the provisions
of the convention in the national, social, economic and legal
framework. 
</P>
</TEXT>
