<HEADLINE> Russia, U.S. Probe into Cooperation in Nuclear Control </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A four-hour discussion held here on
Saturday between Russian Atomic Energy Minister Yevgeny Adamov and
a U.S. delegation focused on possibilities of bilateral
cooperation in control over nuclear technologies.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, the talks had
concentrated on the tightening by both sides over nuclear
technologies in the context of the recent nuclear tests in India
and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
Adamov invited the American side to take technological steps
toward nonproliferation.
</P>
<P>
Head of the U.S. delegation Peter Dominichi, who is satisfied
with the talks, said they also discussed what should be done to
plutonium from dismantled nuclear arms.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the two countries should primarily develop
measures to rule out the repeated use of the plutonium for
military purposes.
</P>
<P>
During the talks Adamov suggested developing an international
project on the natural security of nuclear technologies.
</P>
<P>
This is a very promising project, and agreement and mutual
understanding on it may be reached in time, Dominichi said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed the diluting of military plutonium
for power engineering. However, Russia is not ready for that and
therefore other ways of using the plutonium should be developed,
the American official said.
</P>
<P>
The talks also touched on preparations for the next session of
the Gore-Kiriyenko commission due in Moscow at the end of July,
especially the implementation of a contract for the delivery of
Russian low enriched uranium extracted from dismantled nuclear
warheads.
</P>
<P>
Adamov said that a contract on such deliveries may be signed by
Russia and the U.S. within this month.  
</P>
</TEXT>
