<HEADLINE> ECOWAS Discusses Military Intervention in G. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and defense ministers from
west African countries are at a meeting in Abidjan, capital of
Cote d'Ivoire, to discuss whether to intervene militarily in the
current conflict in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which stated Friday, is called at the request of
Guinea Bissau's President Joau Bernardo Vieira for assistance
from the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) in
the battle to overcome a month-long rebellion by some of the
country's soldiers.
</P>
<P>
It may mean to generate a consensus for sub-regional action in
favor of President Vieira, analysts said here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The worsening situation in that country resulted from a
rebellion led by former Army Chief of Staff Amsumane Mane,
shortly after he was sacked by President Vieira for neglect of
duty on June 6.
</P>
<P>
The country's neighbors, Guinea and Senegal have sent some
2,000 troops to help the Vieira government's efforts to end the
revolt that has killed an unknown number of people in the
country.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the meeting, once the principle
of military intervention is passed, ECOWAS would order its
monitoring group, widely known as ECOMOG, to launch air attack
against the rebel soldiers to expel them from the positions they
hold currently.
</P>
<P>
The ministers will also discuss a plan which asks for the
establishment of a mediation council to solve the crisis in
peaceful means, the sources disclosed.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Foreign Minister Tom Ikimi told the meeting "it's
time we stop all military coups and attempt to make military
coups in the sub-region."
</P>
<P>
Nigeria currently chairs ECOWAS. Its troops led ECOMOG in
successfully reversing a coup in Sierra Leone last February and
restoring the country's elected government.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS Executive Secretary Lansana Kouyate also stressed the
need not to recognize any government empowered through military
coup.
</P>
<P>
Kouyate made consultative visits to Senegal, Gambia and Guinea
later last month to seek solution to the crisis in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
These visits are seen as preparatory steps for the current
meeting. It is not yet known when the meeting will close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
