<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Defends Deal About Nigeria's Abiola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- United Nations Secretary-General
Kofi Annan has defended a deal to obtain Nigerian politician
Moshood Abiola's release from detention in Nigeria, saying the
situation in the country had changed since the 1993 presidential
polls which was apparently won by Abiola.
</P>
<P>
According to a report reaching here Saturday, Annan made the
remarks Friday night before leaving Accra, capital of Ghana, for
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The UN chief said he had spoken to many Nigerians during his
visit to Nigeria and they "did not see Moshood Abiola as a
president-in-waiting".
</P>
<P>
Many things had changed since the June 12, 1993 elections, and
thus the situation should be viewed in the light of the
expectations of both Nigerians at large and the international
community, Annan said.
</P>
<P>
Annan, who arrived his home town Thursday after a four-day
visit to Nigeria, said Nigeria's new leader, Gen. Abdulsalam
Abubakar, had agreed to release "all political prisoners" at an
unspecified time.
</P>
<P>
Abiola, after meeting with Annan, had accepted that he would
not claim the right of the presidency, for which he was arrested
by the military government four years ago.
</P>
<P>
But some of his relatives and the country's opposition leaders
expressed disbelief of Abiola's undertaking to renounce his claim
on the presidency in return for freedom.
</P>
<P>
Proper solution of Abiola's case is widely seen as the core to
resolve the current political crisis in Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
The opposition has been pressing the release of Abiola so that
he could organize a government of national unity, but the
military government seems not to agree.  
</P>
</TEXT>
