<HEADLINE> Egypt, France to Continue Joint Mideast Initiative </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A senior French official said here
Saturday that France and Egypt have agreed to continue
consultations on a joint initiative calling for an international
conference to salvage the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, Jean
Claude Consserean, director of the French Foreign Ministry North
Africa and Middle East Department, said their talks were part of
the consultations.
</P>
<P>
The two sides would follow up the initiative and monitor the
situation in the Middle East, said Consserean, who arrived here in
the day for a two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
During a visit to France last May, Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and his French counterpart Jacques Chirac launched the
initiative on calling for an international conference to discuss
the long deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Consserean will hold further talks with Egyptian officials on
Sunday to coordinate the stands of the two countries before a
visit to Washington by Moussa in August.
</P>
<P>
He will leave here late Sunday for Israel for talks with
Israeli officials.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli talks have been stalled since March
1997 due to Israeli construction of a settlement in the Arab East
Jerusalem and the differences over Israeli troop withdrawal from
the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
