<HEADLINE> Egypt Frees 2 Journalists in Libel Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Two journalists from the Egyptian
opposition newspaper Al Shaab were released from prison Saturday
after a court overruled an earlier verdict convicting them of
libel.
</P>
<P>
Magdy Ahmed Hussein, editor-in-chief of the Arabic-language
paper, and Mohamed Helal, an editor, were set free two days after
the Court of Cassation, Egypt's supreme court, overturned a
jailing sentence against them, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
But the news agency did not tell the reason why the earlier
verdict was overruled.
</P>
<P>
Hussein and Helal were sentenced to one year in prison with
hard labor for their articles accusing former Interior Minister
Hassan el-Alfi and his sons of using his position to amass wealth.
</P>
<P>
The two journalists have served four months in jail.
</P>
<P>
Officials of the supreme court said the ruling ordered the
former minister to pay the expenses of the trial.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the court ordered a retrial of another case in which
Al Shaab accused Alaa el-Alfi, son of the ex-minister, of abusing
power to procure land and houses in the Mediterranean city of
Alexandria, MENA said.
</P>
<P>
The former minister was sacked last November after 58 foreign
tourists and four Egyptians were gunned down by terrorists in the
southern tourist city of Luxor. The killing was widely blamed on
lax security. 
</P>
</TEXT>
