<HEADLINE> S. Leone's Junta Leaders to Be Tried in One Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the military junta that
ruled Sierra Leone until last February will face a court martial
in a week, a report reaching here said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Johnny Paul Koroma, the junta's number one leader, is still on
the run, but as many as 70 others, including Koroma's brother and
the junta's chief of defense staff, Brig. Samuel Koroma, could
stand trial.
</P>
<P>
"The long-awaited court martial against the top brass and
junior ranks for the military junta will begin in a week's time,"
a spokesman for restored President Ahemd Tejan Kabbah said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
According to prison sources, about 100 soldiers alleged to be
closely involved with the junta are currently in jail.
</P>
<P>
Also facing trial would be Hassan Konteh, who was Kabbah's
chief of defense staff before the May 25, 1997 military coup,
Brig. Kiss Kamara, the junta's health minister, and Corporal
Tamba Gborie, who announced the coup on the national radio.
</P>
<P>
The junta was driven out of the capital Freetown in
mid-February by the west African peacekeeping force ECOMOG, which
has since been carrying out operations to mop up the remnants of
the junta and allied rebels in the east and north of the tiny
west African country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
