<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-04 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Formula for Resuming Cyprus' Talks Hopeful: U.N. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- A U.N. envoy said here on Saturday
that it is hopeful he will find an "acceptable" formula to help
resume the talks between leaders of Cyprus' two communities when
he returns to the Mediterranean island in September.
</P>
<P>
"I am trying very hard and I can tell you I may succeed. I am
quite hopeful that when I come back we will be able to have a
process again," United Nations Secretary General Kofi Annan's
Special Advisor for Cyprus Diego Cordovez told reporters before
wrapping up a three-day peace mission.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, Cordovez held two separate meetings with
Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash.
</P>
<P>
He said that he had "positive, substantive and constructive"
discussions with the two community leaders, adding that "I am very
satisfied with the progress we have made."
</P>
<P>
It is important to find out the two sides "are willing to
discuss" the resumption of negotiations and "are interested in
discussing with me the possibilities and alternatives" for
resuming the talks.
</P>
<P>
"The main problem in Cyprus is that there is very little
confidence between the two sides, tremendous distrust and the only
way you can reduce distrust is to get them to talk," Cordovez said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides are interested in trying to find a way to resume
the talks, he added.
</P>
<P>
The talks between the Greek Cypriots and the Turkish Cypriots
broke down last summer when Denktash walked out of the
negotiations to protest against European Union's decision to start
accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
"I told them we need a formula that is acceptable to both. It
should be reasonable, practical and fair to both sides," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his mission, Cordovez said his principle task is
to "get a process of negotiations started," a task he will perform
in two phases.
</P>
<P>
At the first stage before September, he will consult his two
interlocutors on the arrangements for the talks to be resumed and
the second stage will start in September after Clerides and
Denktash have thought about the alternatives for the resumption of
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Cordovez said that he will report to the U.N. Security Council
on Monday his "positive and substantive discussions" with the
leaders of Cyprus' two communities and "the good atmosphere on
both sides."
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkey landed its
troops and took over the northern third of the island after a
failed coup by the Greek Cypriots seeking union with Greece.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. has been trying for decades to reunify Cyprus in a
bizonal and bicommunal federation, but so far no tangible results
have been achieved. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
