<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US President Clinton Back Home, Hoping for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton and
his family returned home early Saturday morning, hoping more
regular summits between the United States and China would take
place.
</P>
<P>
Stepping off the "Air Force One" at the Andrews military
airport, the Clintons appeared in high spirit with broad smiles on
their faces.
</P>
<P>
The nine-day trip to China was fascinating, the president said,
hoping more regular meetings would be held between the two
countries' leaders.
</P>
<P>
The visit, the first by an American president in almost ten
years, took Clinton to Xi'an, Beijing, Shanghai, Guilin and Hong
Kong. Before he flew back home, President Clinton told
reporters in Hong Kong that his trip was a remarkable success.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and his Chinese counterpart Jiang Zemin met in Beijing
for continued exchanges on a wide range of issues from bilateral
ties to nonproliferation to human rights. They announced at a
joint press conference that the two countries would not aim
nuclear missiles at each other.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders issued a joint statement calling for
strengthening of the Biological Weapons Convention and early
conclusion of a protocol establishing a practical and effective
compliance mechanism and improving transparency.
</P>
<P>
They also agreed to work together to accelerate global
humanitarian demining and ease the tension in South Asia built up
following nuclear tests by India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the two sides identified such areas as energy and
environment protection for closer cooperation between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Critics at home grudgingly acknowledged that President
Clinton's visit was a success.
</P>
<P>
"As a political matter, there seems to be a consensus among
Republicans that, at least for now, Mr. Clinton has overcome fears
among Democrats that the trip would expose the President to
damaging attacks on issues like human rights, the exporting of
satellite technology to China and campaign finance
irregularities," "The New York times" said Friday.
</P>
<P>
House Speaker Newt Gingrich, who had called Clinton to postpone
his trip weeks ago, told reporters Wednesday that "I think the
president did a pretty good job talking on Chinese radio and TV."
</P>
<P>
Administration officials believed that it was significant that
Clinton was accorded unprecedented media coverage in China as he
spoke about such issues as human rights.
</P>
<P>
Both China and the United States hoped that Clinton's visit
would give a new impetus to the improvement of the bilateral
relationship. They try to expand their cooperation while openly
discussing their differences on human rights, Tibet and trade
imbalance issues. 
</P>
</TEXT>
