<HEADLINE> TUC Urges Government To Tackle Economic Slowdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Trades Union Congress (TUC)
urges the government to start talks with employers and trade
unions on how to protect its economy from "stagflation".
</P>
<P>
Low growth and investment, rising unemployment and high price
inflation present an increasing danger, the TUC warns in its
latest economic briefing report.
</P>
<P>
The report says: "The economic slowdown and coming rise in
unemployment is in danger of pushing the government's economic and
labor market strategies off course."
</P>
<P>
It complains that while Chancellor Gordon Brown has taken the
lead in starting a national debate with business leaders on the
causes and cures of low productivity, he has done nothing yet
"beyond exhortation to promote the equally important national
debate on how to reconcile growth, employment and low inflation".
</P>
<P>
The TUC says: "predictions of an immediate slump in the demand
for labor are exaggerated", adding that "there is no doubt the
labor market is fast approaching a turning point."
</P>
<P>
The report indicates job prospects for young workers are
holding up well. However, among the over-50 year olds,
unemployment is rising.
</P>
<P>
"These appear to be among the first labor market casualties of
the economic squeeze applied by tight monetary and fiscal policy,"
the TUC says.
</P>
<P>
It adds the the decline in output has ensured slower
productivity growth and has put a "severe upward pressure on unit
labor costs".  
</P>
</TEXT>
