<HEADLINE> Ethiopia's Foreign Trade Increases via Djibouti </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Business activities in the
eastern part of Ethiopia has flourished since Ethiopia recently
began to fully carry out import and export trade via Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
Tewolde Gebre-Amlak, office manager of the National Bank of
Ethiopia in Dire Dawa, second largest city in Ethiopia which
located at middle of the 781 kilometers Djibouti-Addis Ababa
railway, said that ever since Ethiopia's import-export was
channeled fully via the Djibouti port, the volume of imported
items has shown an increase of about 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
Tewolde said earlier Ethiopia used to effect only 30 percent
of its import-export transaction via the Djibouti port, the
Ethiopian News Agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He said the businessmen now have better access to
infrastructures than they used to when effecting their business
via Assab and Massawa ports.
</P>
<P>
Ethiopia has diverted from Assab port of Eritrea to port of
Djibouti as its outlet since the outbreak of Ethio-Eritrea border
dispute on May 6, this year. About 70 percent of Ethiopia's
import-export used to transit through Assab.  
</P>
</TEXT>
