<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair on
Saturday urged both sides in Northern Ireland to stay calm and
search for an agreement to ease off potential conflict to be
sparked by Sunday's parade.
</P>
<P>
"I say to both sides: carry on searching for an agreement, for
a negotiated solution, and keep calm and keep law-abiding because
this is bound to be exploited by small pockets of extremists on
both sides who want to wreck the (peace) agreement," Blair
appealed to Northern Irish people in an interview with Sky TV.
</P>
<P>
Blair was speaking on the eve of Sunday's parade by Protestant
Orangemen who insisted to go ahead with the traditional march in
Protadown in defiance of a ban issued by the independent Parade
Committee early this week. But Catholic residents in the city vow
to oppose them.
</P>
<P>
"It's important for people to realize this is a problem this
year with this particular march... but it doesn't mean anything in
respect of the wider picture unless people force it that way," he
added. In the past two years, such parades have sparked off riots
between Protestants and Catholics.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister, who paid a visit to Belfast on Thursday to
head off the crisis, said the stand-off had arisen in Portadown
because of an unwillingness by both sides of the divided community
to talk to one another.
</P>
<P>
But he believed an agreement was still possible to settle the
problem peacefully if there was a dialogue.
</P>
<P>
"If it was left up to the leaders of those parties involved in
the talks process in Northern Ireland, I have no doubt that we
would have an agreement."
</P>
<P>
Blair also promised to keep doing all he could to head off a
repeat of the trouble that the annual parade has sparked in each
of the past two years. 
</P>
