<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyber Courtesy Highlighted in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, July 4 (Xinhua)-- Singapore on Saturday highlighted
courtesy in cyberspace, as it launched its 21th national courtesy
campaign.
</P>
<P>
At the launch of the 1998 National Courtesy Campaign, Finance
Minister Richard Hu said the Singapore Courtesy Council wants to
promote the campaign to the growing generation of cybernauts.
</P>
<P>
"As we progress into the era of the Internet, reinforcing the
courtesy message is going to be even more crucial," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is especially so when conveniences such as e-mail and
e-commerce are becoming so much a part of our lives", he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the Courtesy Council's overall theme this year focuses
on promoting good neighborliness.
</P>
<P>
"This is very relevant, especially at a time when we are facing
a slowdown in our economy", he emphasized.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Singapore Courtesy Council Noel Hon also said
the current campaign pays special attention to the use of pagers
and handphones and etiquette on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
"With 2.3 million handphones and pagers in Singapore, this
could become a very serious problem", he said, referring to the
rising complaints about the inappropriate use of handphones and
pagers at concerts, in cinemas, theaters and weddings.
</P>
<P>
"Another new norm of behavior that comes from technology is
etiquette on the Internet", he said.
</P>
<P>
The National Courtesy Campaign was first launched in 1979 and
the focus was on courteous behavior toward each other under its
first slogan of "Courtesy is Our Way of Life."
</P>
<P>
The Courtesy Council has designed 19 interstitials that cover
the years since then, playing an important part in bringing about
harmony in the country's society.
</P>
<P>
Summing up the campaigns over the years, Minister Hu said the
they have changed in terms of length, focus and choice of target
audience, changing from a month-long campaign to a year-long
drive, from a government-led effort to a campaign driven more by
private initiatives, from getting people to be courteous in a
vague sense to urging them to make the first move to practise
small acts of kindness every day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
