<HEADLINE> Jordanian, Egyptian, Palestinian Leaders to Meet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 4 (Xinhua) -- King Hussein of Jordan will leave
here Sunday for Cairo to meet Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to discuss ways to restart the
Mideast peace process.
</P>
<P>
They would seek how to press Israel into accepting a United
States proposal that calls for a 13.1 percent second-phase
redeployment of Israeli troops in the West Bank, Jordan's official
news agency reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting will also focus on the recent Israeli government's
decision to annex new parts of the Holy City of Jerusalem, which,
if not reverted, would change the geographic and demographic
situation of the city in benefit of the Jewish inhabitants, the
news agency said.
</P>
<P>
Besides peace issues, the three leaders are to discuss means of
enhancing economic cooperation between their countries,
particularly in the field of trade exchange and investment.
</P>
<P>
King Hussein's trip to Cairo will be a "short working visit"
upon an official invitation from Mubarak, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations have been deadlocked
since March 1997 due to the Jewish settlement expansion in the
Arab East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In order to defuse the tension and revive peace talks between
the two sides, the U.S. put forward the proposal mentioned above
several months ago. The Palestinians accepted it, but Israel
rejected it.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt, the only two Arab countries that have reached
peace accords with Israel, have been active mediators in the Middle
East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
