<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Find Salmonella-resistant Gene in Chickens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- British scientists have identified
the gene that keeps chickens free of salmonella, the bacterium
that can cause human food poisoning, The Times newspaper said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The discovery, made by researchers at the Institute for Animal
Health at Compton, Berkshire, could lead to the elimination of
salmonella in eggs and the fall in food-poisoning cases.
</P>
<P>
The salmonella-resistant gene, thought to be present in about
10 percent of commercial chickens, increases the bacteria-killing
powers of macrophages, large cells that form part of the chicken's
immune system.
</P>
<P>
Scientists are now working on a way to identify the DNA markers
for the gene, hoping that in a few years it should be possible for
commercial breeders to identify chickens with the gene by a simple
blood test.
</P>
<P>
"We are on the brink of potentially controlling salmonellosis,
which would improve food safety and reduce the loss of valuable
stock." Phil Jones, head of microbiology at the institute, was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
While properly cooking eggs could kill the salmonella bacteria,
the highest risk comes from food made from raw eggs. Last year
32,000 cases of salmonella poisoning were reported in England and
Wales, 48 of them fatal.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finances Uganda in Flashing Out Elephants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) has
offered Uganda 250,000 U.S. Dollars to help flash out elephants
which have been disrupting the normal lives of people in central
part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The Second Deputy Prime Minister and Minister of Tourism Moses
Ali said at Luwero district Saturday, that experts have already
started monitoring the elephants which walk into the villages,
adding that an aerial survey will be conducted to establish the
whereabouts of the annoying elephants, Radio Uganda reported.
</P>
<P>
Local people are assured that the government will translocate
the giant elephants into national parks and a foreign expert will
come to embark on the work soon.
</P>
<P>
The deputy prime minister urged people to cooperate by
offering correct information about the destruction of crops and
loss of lives caused by the elephants.
</P>
<P>
Recently there have been some newspaper reports about the
misdoings of elephants which strayed into populated areas or crop
fields, destroying crops and killing the vulnerable. This is the
first time in recent months for the government to use foreign
assistance in flashing out the big animals. 
</P>
