<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
Tunis -- The percentage of the Tunisian debts declined from 53
of the GNP in 1991 to 51 in 1996, according to the local economic
daily "El-Sabah" Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The daily predicted that the trend would go on until the
percentage reaches 40 in 2001. Tunisia is one of the few countries
in the Arab and African regions which did not resort to
rescheduling its arrears.
</P>
<P>
Tunis -- The internation stock exchange federation and the Arab
money market authority will hold a meeting here between July 8 and
10 under the title "investment in Arab exchanges .. opportunities
and challenges."
</P>
<P>
Represtatives of capital markets in Tunisia, Kuwait, Egypt,
Lebanon, Morocco, Bahrain, Jordan, Qatar, Palestine and Sudan will
take part in the event.
</P>
<P>
According to the sources of the Tunis Stock Exchange, the
meeting will discuss two themes namely; the external effects on
the Arab stock exchanges and ways of facing up to them, and the
nature of the Arab capital markets and investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- An exhibition of Saudi-made products was unveiled here
Saturday to acquaint the Jordanians with such products.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Minister of Industry and Trade Hani Mulqi and his
Saudi Arabia counterpart Osama Faqih cut the ribbon for the
six-day show.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the volume of Jordanian exports to Saudi Arabia
reached 141 million Jordanian dinars (about 199 million dollars)
and the imports from Saudi Arabia 110 million dinars (about 155
million dollars), Jordan's official Petra news agency reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
