<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Israeli Allied Militiamen Wounded in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Two members of the Israeli allied
South Lebanese Army (SLA) were wounded in south Lebanon in two
separate incidents Saturday, the Voice of the People radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The first SLA militiaman was moderately wounded in a roadside
bomb detonated by the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
near Kfar Tibnit village on the edge of Israeli occupied south
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The second one was wounded when his car which was carrying the
first wounded SLA man, turned over in the eastern sector of the
occupied zone, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
The wounded SLA members were then carried away by an Israeli
helicopter to a hospital in Israel, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer border strip in
south Lebanon in 1985 to guard its northern areas against
cross-border attack by guerrillas, clashes with Lebanese
guerrillas spearheaded by Hezbollah have never stopped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
