<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northern Ireland Police Chief Stands Firm over Parade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Protestant Orangemen would not be
allowed to march through the mainly nationalist area of Portadown
on Sunday, even if they force a stand-off, a police chief said on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Chief Constable Ronnie Flanagan said he was determined to
enforce a decision to prevent loyalists from passing along the
Garvaghy Road from Drumcree church.
</P>
<P>
"The march will not be forced down" the road, BBC quoted him as
saying in Portadown.
</P>
<P>
The Orangemen were determined to march the route despite a
ruling by an independent parades commission that it should be
diverted away from Garvaghy Road. In the past two years, Orangemen
and police conflicted while the parade was going on.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, British soldiers threw a ring of concrete, razor
wire and armored cars around the Catholic-dominated area on
Saturday to keep back the Orangemen.
</P>
<P>
Irish nationalists who live on Garvaghy Road plan to block it
even though security forces used force to clear them last year,
allowing the Orangemen to proceed.
</P>
<P>
In face of the possible riot on Sunday, Protestant First
Minister David Trimble and his nationalist, Catholic deputy
elected at the inaugural meeting of a new power-sharing assembly
last week issued a joint appeal for calm.
</P>
<P>
"We do not want to see the two sides in our community embark on
a collision course where there will only be losers," Trimble said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
