<HEADLINE> Zambia Reiterates to Sell Copper Mines in Full </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba reiterated Saturday that his country will sell its copper
mines in full value.
</P>
<P>
Opening this year's Zambia International Trade Fair in Ndola,
northern Zambia, Chiluba reiterated the need to get full value of
the Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines (ZCCM) in its on-going
privatization.
</P>
<P>
He said successful privatization of ZCCM will contribute to
the government and job creation will depend on increased
activities of the ZCCM, the biggest foreign exchange earner of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Chiluba urged foreign investors not to doubt his government
resolve to create private sector-driven economy.
</P>
<P>
Zambia discontinued the negotiations last April with Kafue
Consortium on the sale of Nchanga and Nkana mines, which make up
65 percent of the ZCCM assets, over disagreement on the prices of
the two mines.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, two other foreign mining companies pulled out, citing
falling international copper prices as the main reason for their
withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
Last month, donors pledged Zambia an aid of 530 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
However, some donors said recently that they will not release
the pledged aid until ZCCM is privatized because the money ZCCM
is losing equals the amount of the aid the donor community
pledged to give Zambia and that if it is released, it will go to
bailing out the ailing ZCCM.  
</P>
</TEXT>
