<HEADLINE> Tanzanian Cotton Exports Benefitted from </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 4 (Xinhua) - Tanzanian cotton exports are
expected to fetch good prices this season as a result of the
international economic sanctions imposed against India and
Pakistan for their nuclear testings, an official said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Ernest Nyanda, Chairman of the Tanzania Cotton Lint and Seed
Board of Directors (TCL &AMP; SB) said in a statement reaching here
that the cotton growers in the Lake Victoria areas were
encouraged by the sanctions on India and Pakistan which are both
main cotton producers in the world market.
</P>
<P>
He said that the world demand for lint this year stands at
89.036 million bales compared with a target of 87.036, meaning
that buyers should give competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
He said that cotton buyers have offered between 160-210
Shillings (0.24-0.35 U.S. Dollars) per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
Nyanda also cautioned both peasants and buyers of cotton, in
his recent tour of Mara, Shinyanga and Mwanza regions, that
Tanzania was in danger of being kicked out of the world market
because of the decline in the quality of its cotton since the
liberalization of the marketing of the crop in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Serious steps will be taken to improve the mis-management of
cotton in the buying centers, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
