<HEADLINE> Surfing Net from Home Overtakes Use at Work in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 4 (Xinhua) -- For the first time people using the
Internet from home in Britain outnumber those net surfing at work,
according to a new research.
</P>
<P>
The findings, coming from the latest Internet Monitor, a
quarterly survey of 1,000 Internet users, showed that 4.4 million
people in Britain have used the Internet in the last six months,
of which 40 percent or 2.2 million people logged on from home.
</P>
<P>
Around 36 percent accessed the Internet from work with the
remainder logging on at Internet cafes, clubs and libraries.
</P>
<P>
The results mark a watershed in the evolution of the Internet
as it switches from being a tool for business to being a medium
for domestic consumers.
</P>
<P>
The increase in home use has been matched by a growth in people
using the Internet for home shopping, with one million people
buying something over the Internet in the last six months.
</P>
<P>
The average Internet shopper spends around 40 pounds (66 U.S.
dollars) per month and more than half feel confident about using
their credit card over the Internet, the research has found.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
