<HEADLINE> Sudanese President Denounces Bombings in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KHARTOUM, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Sudanese President Omar Hassan
Ahmed al-Bashir Saturday condemned the bombings that took place in
the capital area before the ninth anniversary of the Salvation
Revolution on June 30.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a rally in Atbara city to the north of the capital,
al-Bashir vowed to punish those responsible for the crimes of the
kind.
</P>
<P>
Nine bombings occurred last week in the area, setting ablaze a
gas station, damaging an electricity facilities and cutting a
power network between the capital and El-Damazin.
</P>
<P>
The bombings that targeted strategic public utilities in the
province resulted from the "failure of the enemies of religion"
and were carried out by hostile elements to harm Sudan and its
"civilizational project," al-Bashir said.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese president stressed that the enemies are destined
to failure in their plot to destabilize Sudan through various
"aggressive designs."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Mohammed Abdul-Rahim Gah-Ennabi, director of Sudan's
Criminal Evidence Department and Central Investigations, urged the
citizens to keep vigilant against such crimes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
