<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Deputy PM Criticizes Those Against Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Uganda Second Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister of Tourism, Trade and Industry Moses Ali
Saturday criticized those who are inciting the public against the
land bill.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks in response to a song sung at the 76th
International Cooperative Day celebrations at the Luwero Sports
Ground in central Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Those who are mobilizing young people to incite the public
should stop it immediately because it would be a potential danger
in future, he warned.
</P>
<P>
He said the land bill, passed by the parliament at the end of
June and consented by President Yoweri Museveni on July 2, is a
law now which must be strictly enacted.
</P>
<P>
The peaceful resolution of the land bill in parliament shows
the country is mature in all aspects, he added.
</P>
<P>
The land bill, passed by the parliament after eight days of
steamy debate, provides security for both tenants and land owners
and is therefore vital to further development of the country's
growing economy.
</P>
<P>
It was originally protested by the Buganda Kingdom which
thought that the central government was to take land away from
the kingdom through the bill.
</P>
<P>
With discussions between President Museveni and
parliamentarians representing the kingdom, the problem was
resolved peacefully.  
</P>
</TEXT>
