<HEADLINE> 4thlead: People Retreat From Tremor-hit Southern </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- People are fleeing from Adana,
southern Turkey, after 1,000 people were injured in two
earthquakes Saturday, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The injured have been rushed to hospitals.
</P>
<P>
The earthquakes measured 5.1 and 4.4 degrees on the Richter
scale.
</P>
<P>
The agency said bus and railway stations in Adana are full of
crowds waiting to leave the quake-stricken region.
</P>
<P>
Following the strong earthquake measuring 6.3 degrees on the
open-ended Richter scale on June 27, the people in Adana started
to return home gradually from their makeshift tents in the open
area, said the agency.
</P>
<P>
Reports said that many people were injured after jumping from
their balconies and some others suffered heart attack in great
panic.
</P>
<P>
The quakes in Adana are the strongest of more than 70
aftershocks after the previous tremor a week ago, which killed at
least 140 people and injuring more than 1,500 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
