<HEADLINE> Egypt, Jordan, Palestine to Host Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Jordanian King Hussein will
hold talks here on Sunday on the stalled Mideast peace process,
Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The tripartite summit will focus on the latest developments of
the peace process and the deteriorating conditions in the occupied
Palestinian territories, Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The leaders will discuss a United States proposal on Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank, Moussa added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has reportedly proposed that Israel hand over another
13.1 percent of the West Bank to the Palestinian National
Authority. The Palestinians have accepted the proposal, but Israel
has not.
</P>
<P>
The summit will also discuss Israel's recent decision to expand
the authority of Jerusalem, which will cover eight West Bank
settlements to east, north and south of the city, the Egyptian
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Arabs fear that the plan will change Jerusalem's geographical
and demographic status.
</P>
<P>
The three leaders will touch on means of strengthening economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador in Cairo Zohdi al Kedra said that Arafat
will hold talks with Mubarak before the tripartite summit on the
recent clashes in the Gaza Strip between the Palestinians and
Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
A confrontation erupted Thursday over control of a road in the
Gaza Strip. Israel sealed off the Gaza Strip and refused
Palestinian Minister of Communications Emad Falouji and other
officials to enter Gaza through the Eretz check point.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Palestinian police ordered dozens of trucks to
block roads leading to Jewish settlements. Israeli troops also
stationed three vehicles on a road linking two major cities in the
Gaza Strip and created a serious traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
"This standoff indicated that the patience of the Palestinian
people is running thin of (Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin)
Netanyahu's provocations and attempts to outflank the peace
agreements," Kedra said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
