<HEADLINE> Russia Issues Note of Protest to South Korea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Russian Foreign Ministry on
Saturday issued an official note to South Korean ambassador Li In
Ho to protest unlawful activities of a councillor of the embassy,
according to the Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Russia's Federal Security Service (FSB) last night detained
councillor of the South Korean embassy Cho Sung U, who was
allegedly in secret meeting with a Russian Foreign Ministry
official.
</P>
<P>
The press service of the Federal Security Service said on
Saturday that his detention became possible due to long and
thorough intelligence work with the assistance of the Foreign
Ministry's Security Directorate.
</P>
<P>
The Russian side believes the activities of the South Korean
diplomat were incompatible with a diplomatic status.
</P>
<P>
According to Itar-Tass news agency, it has been established
that the Russian contact systematically provided confidential
information to the South Korean secret services, thus causing
substantial damage to Russia's political and economic interests.
</P>
<P>
Cho Sung U was handed over to embassy officials after he had
completed all formalities at FSB, Itar-Tass said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the FSB instituted criminal proceedings
against the Russian accomplice.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean diplomat was invited to leave Russia within
three days, the report said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
