<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- An Arab League (AL) official said Sunday that the
number of Arab countries, which have enforced the first phase of
the Greater Arab Free Trade Zone Agreement, had risen to 11.
</P>
<P>
The AL Assistant Secretary-General for Economic Affairs Abdul
Ruhman al-Sahybani said that these countries were putting into
effect the executive program of the pact, which involved a 10
percent cut in tariffs starting from last January.
</P>
<P>
Trade exchange among these states accounts for around 80
percent of inter-Arab trade.
</P>
<P>
Signatories to the pact are committed to phasing out customs
duties by the end of the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
TUNIS -- Tunisia plans to attract more foreign tourists,
especially Germans and Britons, in a bid to further promote its
tourism industry through an advertisement campaign.
</P>
<P>
A study conducted by a state-run institution pointed out that
23 million Britons and 10 million Germans intend to visit Tunisia,
and huge potentials exist in eastern Europe where people are
getting richer.
</P>
<P>
The study also recommended working out policies and strategies
to bring the country's tourism industry in line with the
international changes in the related areas of technology,
marketing and communication.
</P>
<P>
The tourist sector is a major source of hard currency in
Tunisia as its revenues hit 1.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1997.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt and Iran have reached an agreement to set up a
joint company to market and export pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
The company will market Iranian medicines in Arab and African
countries and Iran will market Egyptian pharmaceutical products in
Asia and Russia.
</P>
<P>
Gamila Moussa, undersecretary of the Egyptian Ministry of
Health for pharmaceutical affairs, said following her return from
Tehran Saturday, that the two sides also signed an agreement on
health and medicinal cooperation.
</P>
<P>
They agreed on exchange of information, staff training and
joint research in health and medical fields. Egypt has accepted an
Iranian proposal to set up joint industries for manufacturing
medical equipments which will then be marketed in both countries,
she said.
</P>
<P>
ALGIERS -- The Algerian Minister of Small and Medium-sized
Enterprises Bouguerra Sultani has announced that the government
will privatize 1,000 public enterprises, selling shares to workers
and staff, in the the coming months.
</P>
<P>
He said the privatization would be completed before the end of
the year. He estimated the number of bankrupt public
establishments and factories due to mismanagement in Algeria at
1,200.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Ministry of Agriculture is undertaking a
study on the needs of the Iraqi Ministry of Agriculture for
Egyptian animal fodder for cattle, poultry and sheep, Sunday's
local newspaper "Alam Al Yom" reported.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian First Undersecretary of State for Agriculture Ali
Saada has disclosed that the export of fodder will not be
restricted to government agencies, but to the private sector as
well.
</P>
<P>
An Egyptian trade delegation had recently visited Iraq for
talks with Iraqi officials on prospective exports of Egyptian
foodstuffs and medicine to Iraq under the oil-for-food agreement.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egypt's wheat output reached 6.1 million tonnes this
year, 300,000 tonnes more than last year, Egypt's Middle East News
Agency reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Youssef Wali, minister of agriculture and land reclamation,
attributed the increase to the use of high-yield and
pest-resistant strains.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a meeting with the board of the Agricultural
Ministry's Research Center, the minister also cited a 1 percent
increase in rice production compared with that of last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
