<HEADLINE> Water Rising At Slower Rate On Middle Reaches Of Yangtze </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The flood waters on the middle
reaches of China's Yangtze River, which went above the warning level
on July 2, have started to slow down, an official at the Yangtze
River Flood Headquarters reports, but says that the overall flood
situation is still very serious.
</P>
<P>
He said that a great deal of attention needs to be paid to
banks along the middle reaches of the river, even though no
section has collapsed so far, thanks to the combined efforts of
rescue workers, local residents, and PLA units stationed along the
river.
</P>
<P>
He said that flood-control departments are keeping an eye on
the weather situation in the Three Gorges dam area and along the
upper reaches of the Yangtze. Local officials are anticipating a
struggle with more serious flood as the bulk of the flood season
usually comes in July and August.
</P>
<P>
The latest news from southwest China's Sichuan Province, at the
upper reaches of the Yangtze River, shows that last night the
province was hit by a rainstorm which inflicted heavy losses on
local residents.
</P>
<P>
In less than 24 hours, the rainfall in Wenjiang County and
Shuangliu County, both in Sichuan, reached 350 mm and 240 mm
respectively, which has recent rare in decades. 
</P>
</TEXT>
