<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Trying to Increase Tax Revenues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- China's State Tax Administration
has a series of measures that are intended to bring this year's
tax revenues up by 80 billion to 100 billion yuan (about 12
billion US dollars) over that of last year.
</P>
<P>
This may be hard to achieve because tax revenue for the first
five months of this year were only about 304 billion yuan,
according to an official from the administration.
</P>
<P>
The drop was triggered by the Asian financial crisis, a
decrease in companies' efficiency, a drop in sales, and a slowdown
in exports.
</P>
<P>
To reverse the trend, the State Tax Administration has started
a nationwide three-month tax registration inspection to prevent
tax evasion. Special attention will be paid to key tax sources
like tobacco, alcohol, and electric power.
</P>
<P>
By the end of May, enterprises still owed as much as 44.7
billion yuan in unpaid taxes and overdue fines, and local
governments are being told not to give tax exemptions for
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Value-added tax policies for small businesses will be improved
and the valued-added tax rate has been reduced from 6 to 4 percent
since July 1. Transportation fees for the value added tax are down
from 10 to 7 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
