<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal PM to Meet SAARC Leaders Over Regional Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Girija
Prasad Koirala said Sunday he will discuss separately with all the
other South Asian leaders the issue of stability and security in
the region during their summit meeting late this month.
</P>
<P>
The 10th summit of the South Asian Association for Regional
Cooperation (SAARC) is scheduled to take place in Colombo, Sri
Lanka on July 29-31.
</P>
<P>
Koirala made the remarks when meeting with Akram Zaki, the
special envoy of Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif. Zaki
arrived here Saturday on a mission to brief Nepali leaders about
his country's perception of the current situation in South Asia
after the nuclear tests carried out by India and Pakistan in May.
</P>
<P>
The envoy will also visit Bangladesh, Sri Lanka and the
Maldives.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Zaki handed over a letter from Prime
Minister Sharif to Prime Minister Koirala, the Nepali Foreign
Ministry said, adding that the contents of the letter covered "the
strengthening of matters of regional stability."
</P>
<P>
The nuclear tests by India and Pakistan have raised fears of an
arms race and caused rising tensions in the region. The two
neighbors have fought three wars since their independence in 1947.
</P>
<P>
No further details of the meeting were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
