<HEADLINE> Seoul Voices Regret over Moscow's Expulsion of Diplomat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, July 5 (Xinhua) -- South Korea Sunday expressed regret over
the Russian government's decision to expel a South Korean diplomat on
spy charge Saturday.
</P>
<P>
"It is regrettable for Russia to take such a measure without prior
consultations with us," said Lee Ho-jin, spokesman of the Foreign
Affairs and Trade Ministry.
</P>
<P>
The Russian government Saturday ordered Cho Sung-woo, a councilor
at the South Korea's Embassy in Moscow, to depart Russia within 72
hours after he was detained on charges of espionage activity Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Russia announced that it seized Cho when he met with a Russian, an
employee with Russia's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, who has been
arrested on charge of "providing confidential information'' to South
Korean intelligence."
</P>
<P>
"We will first look into the case as soon as Cho returns home from
Moscow," the spokesman said, adding Seoul will take appropriate
action after its probe.
</P>
<P>
The South Korean Foreign Affairs and Trade Ministry is expected
to call in ambassador to Russia back to Seoul in the coming week.
</P>
<P>
Analysts predicted that South Korea would take retaliatory action
against Russia.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time for either Seoul or Moscow to expel a
diplomat on charges of espionage since the two nations established
diplomatic ties in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
