<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 14:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab Leaders Urge Continuous Efforts to Save Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak,
Jordan's King Hussein and Palestinian National Authority President
Yasser Arafat Sunday joined in a call for unremitting efforts to
put the derailed Mideast peace process back on track.
</P>
<P>
The three Arab leaders made the appeal at a joint press
conference following their meeting at Al-Itihadiya Presidential
Palace here to discuss the latest developments in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
They warned that the region is in a "very dangerous" situation
due to the breakdown in the peace march caused by Israel's
intransigent policy.
</P>
<P>
They urged the Israeli government to implement the agreements
it signed with Arab countries and revise its policy which they
said is "not conducive to stability and security" in the Middle
East.
</P>
<P>
The three-way press conference is considered a rarity because
Hussein and Arafat made lightning visits to Cairo on regular basis
but they seldom appeared together with Mubarak before the press.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president told reporters that he is "deeply
worried" that if the current situation further deteriorates, a
flare-up of violence will be inevitable.
</P>
<P>
"The only road to stability is achieving peace and restoring
the illegitimate rights to the Palestinian people," he said.
</P>
<P>
Despite his serious warnings, Mubarak said an widely-expected
Arab summit will not be convened until the situation hits a dead
end.
</P>
<P>
"If the American initiative fails, there is still the
Franco-Egyptian initiative in place," he said, referring to a
joint call made by French President Jacques Chirac and himself for
an international conference on saving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The call came after Israel resisted a U.S. proposal on Israeli
army withdrawal from 13.1 percent more of the West Bank in its
second phase redeployment. The Palestinians have accepted the
formula.
</P>
<P>
Arafat said he hoped that the tripartite summit will become a
prelude to another pan-Arab summit to coordinate stances of fellow
Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli plan to expand Jerusalem, the Jordanian king noted,
is "the most serious" problem facing the Arab nation. He said all
kinds of attempt to change the status quos of the holy city should
be stopped.
</P>
<P>
In a post-summit communique, the three leaders voiced their
resolute rejection of the Judaization of Jerusalem, calling for a
freeze on Jewish settlement construction and the confiscation of
Palestinian buildings and properties.
</P>
<P>
They demanded that Israel comply with of the land-for-peace
principle which started the peace wheel in the Mideast region
seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
They reiterated that the only way to salvage peace is to carry
out "the spirit of the 1991 Madrid peace conference" and the
relevant United Nations resolutions, and for Israel to return
occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
The summit took place on the heels of the recent standoff in
the Gaza Strip between the Palestinian and Israeli security forces.
</P>
<P>
The tension began Thursday afternoon when Palestinian police
and civilians blocked access to the Gush Katif Jewish settlement
to protest against Israeli closure of a section of a coastal road
in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Israel had barred a Palestinian minister and a convoy of some
22 trucks from entering Gaza via the road, part of which Israeli
soldiers said was off-limits to Palestinians for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
The standoff ended Friday following intensive mediation
involving Americans and Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
The incident was another indication that the tension between
Israel and the Palestinian side is mounting due to the prolonged
deadlock in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the two sides broke down 16 months ago when
Israel began construction of a Jewish settlement in the Arab East
Jerusalem. The sticking point now is the Israeli refusal to carry
out a long overdue troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to the tension, Israeli government approved a plan
on June 21 to expand the boundaries of the hotly disputed holy
city of Jerusalem, a violation of the agreement that no unilateral
move should be made to change the status pending permanent peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak held brief, separate talks with Arafat and Hussein
Sunday morning before the joint summit meeting.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Hussein, who arrived in Cairo respectively on
Saturday night and at noon on Sunday, had left for home in the
afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
