<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Discussing New Extra Time Format </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- FIFA is discussing a new extra time which
may replace the current "sudden death" approach to encourage more
attacking soccer.
</P>
<P>
FIFA spokesman Keith Cooper said on Sunday that in the new format,
the teams will play a full 30-minute extra time if they tie after 90
minutes.
</P>
<P>
If both sides fail to score in extra time, a penalty shoot-out will
be held to decide the winners.
</P>
<P>
If there are goals, the team which scores the most goals wins the
game while if both sides score the same number of goals, team which
nets the first goal will be the winner.
</P>
<P>
The advantage of the format compared to the "sudden death' is that
the team trailing behind in the extra time have a chance to rally from
behind.
</P>
<P>
He said the format was still in the discussion stage and FIFA would
need experiments to study its effect on the sport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
