<HEADLINE> Shanghai Bank Issues Loans for Re-employment Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Shanghai City United Bank has
become the first in this financial and economic center of China to
provide special loans for the re-employment of laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
One of the bank's latest such loans, at 30,000 yuan, was issued
to nine displaced workers who were having financial difficulties
in opening a service center.
</P>
<P>
Bank president Fu Jianhua has pledged to extended more loans
for the re-employment program, ordering all of the banks' 100
sub-branches to issue at least one loan for the re-employment of
displaced workers.
</P>
<P>
All enterprises set up by laid-off workers and enterprises that
will provide job opportunities to displaced workers can apply to
the bank for re-employment loans, Fu said.
</P>
<P>
The bank, which serves mainly small- and medium-size
enterprises, has also set aside 1.8 million yuan to be used for
discounts to re-employment loans.
</P>
<P>
So far, the bank has issued 16 million yuan to 16 enterprises
organized by laid-off workers, enabling 482 people to find jobs.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the bank has donated 1 million yuan to establish a
re-employment loan risk fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
