<HEADLINE> China's Congress Leader Meets Greece's Parliament President (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Li said that the world is becoming more relaxed after the Cold
War but that there have been regional conflicts from time to time
that constitute a threat to world peace and that peace and
development are still arduous tasks. He also said that China
believes that international disputes should be dealt with through
peaceful negotiations and not through force.
</P>
<P>
China is concerned about the Cyprus issue, Li said, and has
always advocated that Cyprus' independence, sovereignty,
territorial integrity, and non-aligned status should be respected,
and hopes that a just and rational resolution will be reached at an
early date through negotiations and on the basis of resolutions by
the UN General Assembly and the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Li said that the world is moving toward multi-polarization,
which is conducive to world peace, and that the European Union is
playing an important role in safeguarding world peace. He added
that China values its relations with the EU and hopes that the
Euro, which is scheduled to begin next year, will help stablize
the world's finances.
</P>
<P>
Kaklamanis said that both Greece and China are ancient
countries that have made significant contributions to human
civilization, and this visit has allowed him to witness China's
great achievements.
</P>
<P>
China is playing an increasingly important role in
international affairs, he said, and exchanges between the two
parliaments are conducive to the development of state-to-state
relations, and that he hopes to see further contacts between the
two.
</P>
<P>
He arrived here today at the invitation of the NPC Standing
Committee. 
</P>
