<HEADLINE> Somalia's 1998 Grain Yield to Hit 5-Year Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations World Food
Program (WFP) warned Sunday that food will be in short supply in
the months ahead in Somalia where grain harvests this year are
expected "to hit an alarming five-year low."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. agency estimated that Somalia's total cereal output
for 1998 would be 160,000 to 170,000 tons, 60 percent less than
last year's production of 462,000 tons, marking the lowest annual
yield since 1993.
</P>
<P>
During the upcoming Gu crop, which is the country's most
important cereal harvest making up 75 to 80 percent of the annual
cereal yield, "Somali farmers will likely bring in only half the
maize and sorghum harvested last year," said a WFP statement
issued here.
</P>
<P>
In anticipation of a poor Gu harvest, cereal prices have
already increased sharply and will continue to go up in the near
future, said the WFP.
</P>
<P>
The sharp decline of cereal yield is a result of the aftermath
of the El Nino rains and floods late last year and early this
year and the following poor rains this season, the statement
noted.
</P>
<P>
"One of the many setbacks was that when the flood waters
receded, some families who had lost virtually all their food
stocks planted small areas of off season crops," said Ricardo
Cueva, WFP's Deputy Country Director for Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"When the Gu rains eventually arrived, large segments of their
fields were then occupied by these minor crops, leaving little
space for them to cultivate their main harvest," he said.
</P>
<P>
The flood, which engulfed the agriculturally-rich Juba and
Shabelle river valley areas in southern Somalia, left residents
with broken river embankments, destroyed irrigation systems,
heavily silted soil, extensive weed growth, and infestations by
pests.
</P>
<P>
The delayed and abnormally low rains this season made it more
difficult for crops to fully mature, said the WFP.
</P>
<P>
Heavy fighting earlier this year in the Bay region, Somalia's
main "bread basket" area, resulted in the displacement of
thousands of families and the abandonment of large tracts of
agricultural fields.
</P>
<P>
Somalia's only other major cereal harvest, the Deyr crop, was
a virtual failure earlier this year when the torrential floods
and heavy rains swept over the south of the country, bringing in
a mere 42,000-ton output of grain.
</P>
<P>
In previous years, the Deyr has produced more than double this
figure.
</P>
<P>
"There is little doubt that thousands of families will need
our (WFP's) help in the months ahead," said Cueva.
</P>
<P>
"Right now we're finalizing plans for a new emergency
operation to distribute some 5,000 tons of relief food over the
next three months to more than half a million southern Somalis,"
he announced.
</P>
<P>
WFP delivered approximately 15,000 tons of food to more than
one million Somali flood victims from last November to May this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FIFA Criticizes "Flash Interviews" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- FIFA on Sunday criticized the practice of
television and radio "flash" interviews at the end of game for
provoking players and coaches to speak irresponsibilly.
</P>
<P>
FIFA Director of Communication Keith Cooper said: "Sometimes it was
simply not fair. It is provoking them saying something which, given
several minutes of reflection, they would probably not say."
</P>
<P>
He said, "FIFA and all the teams are facing great pressure from the
media for instant comments in so-called 'flash interview' at the end
of the game."
</P>
<P>
Cooper added: "The team come off the pitch and the microphone are
stuck to the noses of the coach and the players... They are provoking
them to say something that they may be subsequently punished for."
</P>
<P>
He was responding to a question about German coach Berti Vogts'
words that the referee for their World Cup quarterfinal against
Croatia was biased because somebody had told him to do so.
</P>
<P>
But Cooper dismissed the comments as "totally nonsense." 
</P>
</TEXT>
