<HEADLINE> Chinese Banks Expect To Provide More Loans for Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese banks will provide more
loans for foreign trade companies in the latter half of the year
to ease the impact of the Asian financial crisis, according to Dai
Xianglong, governor of the People's Bank of China, who spoke at a
national bank and foreign trade co-operation meeting here today.
</P>
<P>
Dai said that financial institutions need to provide more
support to export-oriented enterprises and that exports of key
commodities like machinery and electronic products should be
encouraged and the Bank of China should continue to play a leading
role in supporting foreign economic and trade development. The
Bank of China will add 25 billion yuan (about 3 billion
U.S. dollars) in loans to support various export-oriented
enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Financial support is an indispensable part of foreign economic
and trade development, said Shi Guangsheng, minister of foreign
trade and economic cooperation, adding that it is vital for the
stability of the Chinese currency and economy.
</P>
<P>
Cooperation must be strengthened to reduce the effects of the
Asian financial crisis, and the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation is working out new policies and measures to
stimulate exports, he said. 
</P>
