<HEADLINE> Israel Urged to Reopen Roads in Gaza </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior Palestinian official
Sunday urged Israel's reopening of all closed roads in the Gaza
Strip to Palestinian vehicles to prevent the tense situation from
worsening.
</P>
<P>
Mohammad Dahlan, Palestinian preventive security director in
Gaza, said the standoff between Israeli and Palestinian forces
last Thursday in Gaza is liable to trigger violence against
Israel, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The situation is "still very tense and any more such incidents
can lead to the break of big violence," Dahlan said at the press
conference Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Israel has closed some roads in Gaza, including part of the
coastal road near Gush Katif settlement for what it claimed
"security reasons," and barred a senior Palestinian official and a
convoy of 22 vehicles from entering Gaza via the coastal road.
</P>
<P>
In retaliation, Palestinian police and civilians blocked access
to the Gush Katif Jewish settlement last Thursday to protest the
Israeli closure.
</P>
<P>
Their security forces entered a 15-hour standoff when Israel
sent more troops, armored vehicles and tanks into Gaza as
reinforcement.
</P>
<P>
Tensions were brought to an end Friday after intensive
mediation involving U.S., British, Egyptian officials. But the
roads remain sealed.
</P>
<P>
Dahlan spoke highly of the cooperation between security
officers of the two sides in handling the standoff, saying such
cooperation prevented the incident from running out of control.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted an unnamed Palestinian source as saying that
that Dahlan met head of Israeli army's Southern Command Yom-Tom
Samia Saturday night on roads reopening.
</P>
<P>
The source said the two leaders are to meet Sunday for further
discussion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
