<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Orange Order March Stopped at Barricades </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
LONDON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Orangemen reached
barricades Sunday noon and were halted by the blocks set up by
police and troops to prevent them from marching through a Catholic
area on the outskirts of Portadown in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
The marchers calmly turned back, but many vowed to stay until
they were allowed through to a mainly nationalist area.
</P>
<P>
The standoff followed a peaceful march and service at Drumcree
parish church by the Protestant Orangemen late in the morning.
</P>
<P>
The independent Parades Commission has decided to ban the
Protestant march on the traditional route that include the Catholic
areas in Portadown, southwest of provincial capital Belfast. But
the Orange Order, the organizer of the parade, said it would
exercise its "civil right" to follow its traditional journey back
from Drumcree Church, as it did since 1807.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 troops and police were on hand to prevent the
Orangemen going down Garvaghy Road, in accordance with the Parades
Commission ruling.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Chief Constable in Northern Ireland Ronnie Flanagan
said he was determined to enforce the Parades Commission decision
to bar the Protestant Orangemen from passing along the traditional
route. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
