<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 12:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan, Saudi Arabia to Liberalize Bilateral Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Jordan and Saudi Arabia are making
efforts to liberalize bilateral trade and bolster their economic
and commercial cooperation, the semi-official Jordan Times
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Jordanian Minister of Industry and Trade Hani
Mulqi as saying that a joint Jordanian-Saudi committee will be
established to work towards reaching a free trade agreement at
the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Mulqi made the statement here Saturday after meeting with
visiting Saudi Commerce Minister Osama Ibn Jaafar Bin Ibrahim
Faqih that the establishment of such a committee became ever more
necessary as the bilateral trade reached to 354 million
U.S. dollars last year and is expected to further rise this year.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia is Jordan's second largest trade partner after
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Faqih, in Amman for a Saudi-made products exhibition, also
stressed the importance for mutual recognition of product
specifications and standards adopted by each country.
</P>
<P>
By the end of this year an agreement will be signed on products
specifications and standards that will enable businessmen to
understand each other country's requirements and abide by them.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will also sign an agreement on transportation
by land to facilitate the flow of goods and passengers between the
two countries. Jordan currently has over 100 trucks handling Saudi
Arabia-bound goods.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday, Faqih also met with Jordanian Crown Prince Hassan,
and the two sides emphasized the importance of creating an
Arab Free Trade Zone and promised to contribute to the creation of
such a zone.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rehabilitation Center For Drug Addicts In Southeastern China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- East China's Fujian Province has
established a rehabilitation center for drug addicts in honor of a
hero of the drug wars of the nineteenth century, Lin Zexu.
</P>
<P>
The Zexu Rehabilitation Center is a product of the Lin Zexu
Foundation, a non-government organization that has been involved
in a number of anti-drug campaigns in recent years. Lin was a
minister of the Qing Dynasty who was sent by the emperor to stop
opium trafficking by British businessmen in southern coastal area
in the 1830s.
</P>
<P>
Many Chinese believe that drugs not only harm people's health,
but also damage the nation's spirit.
</P>
<P>
In March, police in Fujian announced that they had dealt with
1,407 drug cases and arrested 1,944 suspects in the province.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
