<HEADLINE> Israel Calls Cairo Summit "Not Helpful" </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- As Egyptian, Jordanian and
Palestinian leaders converged in Cairo to discuss the troubled
peace process, Israel dismissed the three-way summit as "not
helpful" and urged Palestinians to resume direct talks.
</P>
<P>
David Bar-Illan, media adviser to Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, was quoted by Israel Radio as saying
that the Cairo summit would not help advance the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He was commenting on the summit held by Egyptian President
Hosni Mubarak, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Jordan's King
Hussein. They held the meeting to coordinate their stances toward
the Israeli intransigent policies.
</P>
<P>
Bar-Illan criticized the three leaders for attempting to
pressure Israel to make concessions in the negotiations, adding
that the best way to revive the peace process was for the
Palestinians to resume direct talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians have refused to return to the negotiating
table since early last year when Israel began building a Jewish
settlement in the East Jerusalem. The talks are currently stuck by
the dispute over the next Israeli troop redeployment in the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
Top on the Cairo summit were the American initiative on the
Israeli redeployment, the Israeli plan to expand the boundaries of
the disputed holy city of Jerusalem, and a joint Egyptian-French
initiative for holding an international conference to rescue the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian-French proposal was made by French President
Jacques Chirac and Mubarak during the latter's visit to Paris in
last May.
</P>
<P>
As a follow-up to the Paris meeting between the two
presidents, French presidential envoy Jean Claude Consserean met
Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa in Cairo Saturday to discuss
the joint peace bid.
</P>
<P>
Aiming to press Israel to accept the American pullback plan,
Arafat has also been lobbying for support for holding an Arab
summit to confront the Israeli policy.
</P>
<P>
But Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai said Sunday that
the Egyptian-French proposal could not serve as an alternative
to the American initiative.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted him as saying that Israel was continuing
discussions with the U.S. over the redeployment and he hoped that
a solution would be found.
</P>
<P>
Consserean arrived in Israel Sunday for talks with Israeli
officials. Israeli Foreign Ministry Director-General Eitan Bentsur
has said that Israel opposes the Egyptian-French proposal because
Israel would be excluded from such a meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
