<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Somali Faction Leaders Leave for Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A large delegation led by
Mogadishu's main faction leaders, accompanied by Libya's
Ambassador to Somalia, left together for Tripoli Sunday morning
for peace talks in that northern African country.
</P>
<P>
The delegation of more than 40 people, accompanied by Libya's
Ambassador to Somalia Ali-Sayid Ma'tuq, took off from the only
tarmac airport of Ballidogle, 90 km south of the capital, at 9:15
a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
The scope behind the sudden visit to Tripoli is not known.
However, sources close to the top aids of the faction leaders had
characterized the move as a new initiative in which Libya wants
to intervene in the deadlocked peace talks over the formation of
an administration for Somalia's capital and the reopening of the
air and sea ports of Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The sources added that the faction leaders will be attending a
large religious congregation sponsored by Libya's leader Col.
Muammar al-Gaddafi on the occasion of the birth day of Prophet
Mohamed which falls on July 6.
</P>
<P>
The departure of the faction leaders coincided with the
arrival of new uniforms for Hussein Aidid's faction only two days
ago.
</P>
<P>
Even though the source of these uniforms is not disclosed
officially, rumors indicate that they have arrived from Libya
through Djibouti.
</P>
<P>
Dozens of gunmen in these new uniforms are wandering around
the main streets of the capital, especially in south Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
According to sources close to the headquarters of the faction
leaders in Mogadishu, the unexpected departure to Libya followed
a formal 10-day invitation from Col.Gaddaf through Ambassador
Ma'tuq.
</P>
<P>
Ma'tug conveyed the letters of invitation to the faction
leaders including Ali Mahdi Mohamed, Hussein Aidid and Osman Ali
Atto who all together flew from the same airport for the second
time now since the civil war broke out in Somalia seven years
ago.
</P>
<P>
This is the second such visit by Mogadishu's faction leaders
to Libya since the Cairo peace deal was signed last December.
</P>
<P>
However, no fruits seem to be coming out soon from either the
meeting in Tripoli or the peace deal of Cairo itself as each of
the faction leaders is facing serious internal rivalry and
further split within each faction.
</P>
<P>
The faction leaders themselves do not agree on many points.
Particularly, Mohamed and Atto have not been in good terms since
the nine-day long abduction of the International Red Cross aid
workers in north Mogadishu in April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
