<HEADLINE> Ethiopian Telecom to Upgrade Internet Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopian Telecommunications
Corporation (ETC) announced Sunday that it will expand the
capacity of Ethio-Internet services and enable it to serve 14,000
subscribers.
</P>
<P>
A press release issued here by the corporation said that a
tripartite memorandum of understanding was signed Thursday by
Ethiopian Ministry of Economic Development and Cooperation, the
United Nations Development Program (UNDP) and ETC to upgrade the
capacity of internet services at a cost of over 1.3 million U.S.
Dollars.
</P>
<P>
According to the memorandum, some 600,000 U.S. Dollars of the
total fund would be covered by the UNDP internet initiative for
Africa and the remaining 703,303 U.S. Dollars by the corporation.
</P>
<P>
The corporation said in its press release that the project
would create a one-megabite capacity which will make possible the
provision of dependable internet services to eight regional
towns.
</P>
<P>
ETC started internet services in capital Addis Ababa with
thousands of subscribers at the beginning of last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the corporation also announced that it has signed a
contract with Global One to further upgrade the band width of its
existing connection server from 256 kilobites to 512 kilobites
per second to solve the problem of congestion.
</P>
<P>
The corporation has also signed a contract with NEC, a
Japanese company, to upgrade the satellite earth station at
Sullulta which was installed by the same company 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The project also includes the installation of a second
international earth station in Makelle before the end of 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
