<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helen Snow School Set Up in Xi'an </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A "Helen Snow School" was recently
established in Xi'an, capital of northwest China's Shanxi Province
in commemoration of the wife of Edgar Snow, a U.S. reporter and
writer who is known for his "Red Star over China" on the Communist
Party of China in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
Helen and her husband went back to China for visits after 1949
when the CPC gained control of the country, and were warmly
received by Chairman Mao Zedong.
</P>
<P>
The 16,600-sq.m. school was established by Xi'an education
departments and local companies. The school covers everything from
primary school to higher education and will have exchanges with
the United States and Japan, sources say.
</P>
<P>
Helen Snow's niece will be the honorary president of the
school.
</P>
<P>
This is the second school in China named after a
foreigner. China had set up a "Bethune School" in honor of Norman
Bethune, a Canadian doctor who contributed to the revolutionary
cause in China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
