<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Newspaper Praises Clinton's China Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A leading Bangladeshi newspaper
Sunday praised U.S. President Bill Clinton's just-concluded China
visit, saying it is conducive to Asia's stability, of which China
remains an anchor.
</P>
<P>
Both the world and China have changed in the past 26 years
since former U.S. President Richard Nixon "opened the way to
engagement with the world's most populous country" in 1972, The
Independent daily said in an editorial entitled "Clinton's China
Mission."
</P>
<P>
China "has modernized and strengthened its economy, and is
today a power to be reckoned with," the newspaper noted.
"President Clinton during his tour of China from Xi'an to Beijing
to Shanghai must have noted this change."
</P>
<P>
"China has remained an anchor of stability in a region (Asia)
torn by economic slide forcing countries of the region to devalue
their currencies," it said. "The U.S. president had words of
praise for China for its economic stability in the face of the
Japanese yen's weakness and Asia's economic downturn."
</P>
<P>
"He also found common ground with Chinese President Jiang Zemin
on the nuclear issue, disarmament and regional cooperation," it
said.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. president signaled to the Chinese public his policy of
engagement with China at his joint news conference with his
Chinese counterpart and later in an interview with the local
television, the editorial said.
</P>
<P>
"Considering everything, Clinton's visit was an historic one
and will hopefully help bring stability in the region," it
stressed.
</P>
<P>
"The general perception is that in a subtle rearrangement of
its Asian relationship, the the United States is putting China
atop the list ahead of its traditional allies," it continued.
"This has sparked sharp reaction in some countries, notably
India," "but is welcomed by most others."
</P>
<P>
"The world will watch with keen interest how the perceived new
relationship between the only superpower of the post-Cold War era
and the Asian giant develops in the days ahead," the editorial
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
