<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New "No-Sweat" Surgery Helps Heavy Perspirers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 5 (Xinhua) -- For those who suffer from
hyperhydrosis -- excessive perspiration from the palms of hands
and soles of feet and armpits - "no sweat" is a cherished wish.
</P>
<P>
Now their wish can become true with the help of a new surgery
adopted by doctors at the Soroka Hospital in the southern Israeli
city of Beersheba.
</P>
<P>
According to traditional surgical solution, the armpit was
opened to enter the thoracic cavity and nerves that stimulate
excessive sweating from the palms were cut.
</P>
<P>
But the surgery took 45 minutes per armpit, and the patients
needed about two weeks to recover. Also, each armpit had to be
operated on months apart.
</P>
<P>
Today the procedure is carried out by the "keyhole surgery" via
the armpits into the chest, said Professor Abraham Mares, chief of
 pediatric surgery at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
In the surgery, a one-centimeter incision is made at the
armpit for a tiny video camera on a catheter and an electric wire
that cauterizes the trouble-making ganglion (knot of nerves). The
area near the ribs is inflated slightly with carbon dioxide gas
to ease manipulation of the instruments.
</P>
<P>
A special type of glue, which peels away in less than a week,
is used to seal the incisions, so even stitches are unnecessary,
Mares said. The patient is kept overnight for observation, and
sent home. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
