<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS to Use Force to End Rebellion in G. Bissau </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Foreign and defense ministers from
west African countries have ended an emergency meeting with a
resolution to use force to crush the armed rebellion in Guinea
Bissau, a report reaching here said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
At the request of Guinea Bissau's President Joau Bernardo
Vieira, the Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS)
held a two-day ministerial meeting, which started Friday in
Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, to discuss the possibility of military
intervention in the country.
</P>
<P>
The ministers have resolved that ECOWAS member states should
immediately beef up the strength of the organization's monitoring
group, widely known as ECOMOG, as the first step to the use of
force.
</P>
<P>
There are now only soldiers from Nigeria and Ghana serving the
West African Peace-keeping Force (ECOMOG). Member states are
urged to redeem pledges they made long ago for the provision of
logistic support and troops contribution to the sub-regional
peace keeping force, according to a communique issued at the end
of the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The decision to send ECOMOG troops to Guinea Bissau was one of
the key resolutions contained in the communique.
</P>
<P>
According to it, the ministers from 14 out of the 16 ECOWAS
member states reaffirmed their support for the
democratically-elected government of President Vieira.
</P>
<P>
The central objective of ECOWAS intervention would be to
restore peace to that country and reassert the authority of the
elected government.
</P>
<P>
The ministers agreed to work toward realizing this objective
by a combination of three measures: dialog and negotiation,
sanctions and embargo, and the use of force.
</P>
<P>
Urging an immediate halt of hostilities within Guinea Bissau,
the minister established a special committee to ensure the full
implementation of the decisions and recommendations.
</P>
<P>
The committee comprises seven countries, namely, Burkina Faso,
Cote d'Ivoire, Gambia, Guinea, Nigeria and Senegal. It will be
joined by representatives of the Organization of African Unity
and ECOWAS secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The committee will also work to ensure support of the United
Nations Security Council to various measures taken by ECOWAS in
handling issues concerning Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
Guinea and Senegal have sent some 2,000 troops to help the
Vieira government's efforts to end the revolt that has killed
hundreds of civilians, leaving tens of thousands to be refugees.
</P>
<P>
The two countries were praised at the meeting for their prompt
action already taken in Guinea Bissau.
</P>
<P>
The armed rebellion started on June 7 and was led by the
country's former Army Chief of Staff Amsumane Mane who was
dismissed by President Vieira the previous day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
