<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dhaka Makes Progress in Eliminating Child Labor in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh has made history in
eliminating child labor from the labor-intensive garment sector,
The New Nation daily reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"Children (child laborers in the garment sector) are now going
to formal and non-formal educational institutions erasing their
garment-workers' symbol," Commerce and Industries Minister Tofael
Ahmed said while addressing a function held here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
This has been done in line with the implementation of the
tripartite Memorandum of Understanding among the Bangladesh
Garment Manufacturers and Exporters Association, the ILO
(International Labor Organization) and UNICEF (United Nations
Children's Fund), he said.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that 353 learning centers had been set up to
accommodate 9,743 children, accounting for 95 percent of the total
former child laborers in the country's garment sector.
</P>
<P>
A monthly stipend of 300 taka (about 6.4 U.S. dollars) was
being provided to each student, he said.
</P>
<P>
Children who attained 14 years of age were also being provided
with job and other income generating facilities, he added.
</P>
<P>
The minister asked the employers not to accept child laborers
in their garment factories any more.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh "is expected to be compensated by 30 percent more
quota for garment export to the markets abroad," he told the
function, saying that the prerequisite for this was to eliminate
child labor in the sector.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh plans to end all forms of child labor by the year
2010. The International Program on Elimination of Child Labor has
been under effective implementation with donor assistance since
1995, and the program will remove the last vestiges of child labor
from the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
