<HEADLINE> Inflation Shoots up to 6.86 percent in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The annual rate of inflation in
India shot up to 6.86 percent for the week that ended June 20 this
year on sustained increases in prices of primary articles, Press
Trust of India (PTI) said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate based on the wholesale price index (WPI)
shot up by 0.21 percentage points to 6.86 (provisional) from 6.65
percent the previous week. Inflation stood at 5.64 percent in the
corresponding week last year.
</P>
<P>
The upward trend in inflation has gathered momentum in the
current fiscal year and this is the seventh consecutive week
inflation has ruled above the six percent mark. During the first
week of April, it stood at 4.91 percent.
</P>
<P>
The rising inflation rate is maily attributed to rises in
prices of certain primary articles. In the last three months
preceding June 13, prices of potatoes had risen by about 126.7
percent while prices of groundnut oil and mustard oil by 11.1
percent and 18.0 percent respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
