<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 09:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak, Arafat Meet to Discuss Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak and
visiting Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat
met here Sunday morning to discuss the latest developments in the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
Their talks focused on the deteriorating situation in the
occupied Palestinian territories due to Israel's practices against
the Palestinians and attempt to contain them, the Middle East News
Agency (MENA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The MENA did not give further details about their discussion.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi al Kedra said Saturday
night that the two leaders would address the recent standoff in
the Gaza Strip between the Palestinian and Israeli troops.
</P>
<P>
The tension began Thursday afternoon when Palestinian police
and civilians blocked access to the Gush Katif Jewish settlement
to protest against Israeli closure of a section of a coastal road.
</P>
<P>
Israel had barred Palestinian Minister of Supplies Abdul Aziz
Shahin and a convoy of some 22 trucks from entering the Gaza Strip
via the road, part of which Israeli soldiers said was off-limited
to Palestinians for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
Israeli charged that the incident was clearly a provocation
planned by the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
But Kedra said that "this standoff indicated that the patience
of the Palestinian people is running thin with (Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin) Netanyahu's provocations and attempts to
outflank the peace agreements."
</P>
<P>
The standoff ended Friday following intensive mediation
involving Americans and Egyptian officials.
</P>
<P>
The incident was another indication that the tension between
Israel and the Palestinian side is mounting due to the prolonged
deadlock in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
Talks between the two sides broke down 16 months ago when
Israel began the construction of a Jewish settlement in the Arab
East Jerusalem. The sticking point now is Israeli refusal to carry
out a long overdue troop redeployment in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Adding to the tension, Israeli government approved a plan on
June 21 to expand the boundaries of the hotly disputed holy city
of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Arafat meeting preceded a three-way summit starting
later Sunday among Mubarak, Arafat and Jordanian King Hussein. The
three leaders will discuss ways to break the deadlock in the peace
process, intensify Arab unity to confront the Israel's hard-line
policies and enhance economic cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in Cairo Saturday night, Hussein is due here
before noon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
