<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Airport Night Move Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The dramatic overnight move of
the most critical airport operations from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok
started at 5:30 p.m. (09:30 GMT) Sunday as planned.
</P>
<P>
During the next 13 hours, Hong Kong will move all equipment and
 facilities from Kai Tak, the world's third busiest international
passenger airport and busiest international cargo airport some 30
km to the west -- the most critical stage of a five-phase
relocation exercise that lasts three months.
</P>
<P>
The night move is claimed to be the biggest peace-time
operation, which is composed of some 1,100 vehicle movements by
land, sea and air. The bulk of equipment are transported on roads,
plus 14 barge and 30 aircraft movements.
</P>
<P>
A dozen government departments and 65 airlines or
aviation-related businesses take part in the overnight relocation.
Police escort convoys along the designated routes, and some 1,000
policemen have already been deployed to control the traffic.
</P>
<P>
Despite forecast for heavy rains, the Hong Kong Observatory
said Sunday morning that there would be "no adverse weather
condition" that would affect the relocation, scheduled to start
at 5:30 p.m. Sunday and end at 6:30 a.m. Monday, when the first
incoming flight is to land at the new airport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
