<HEADLINE> Former Iranian Commander's Son Seeking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A son of former commander of the
Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps Mohsen Rezaee was not kidnaped
but in fact seeking asylum in the United States, the Iranian daily
Salam reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
An unnamed source was quoted as saying that Ahmad Rezaee's
asylum was a personal issue and did not have any political
motives. The paper denied the claim that Ahmad was kidnaped by the
U.S. National Aeronautical and Space Administration (NASA).
</P>
<P>
On Friday, Ahmad's brother Ali Rezaee refuted a report by The
Voice of America's (VOA's) Persian program that Ahmad had sought
asylum in the U.S., claiming that Ahmad was kidnaped by the NASA.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the officials Iranian news agency
IRNA, Ali said that his 21-year-old brother Ahmad phoned home on
Friday, "telling us that he had been threatened to give an
interview with the VOA on Iranian supreme leader" Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
The evening daily Kayhan reported on Saturday that Ahmad left
Iran for the United Arab Emirates (UAE) due to a quarrel with his
father Mohsen, present secretary of the State Expediency Council.
</P>
<P>
In the UAE, Ahmad, a sophomore studying mathematics at Tehran's
Teacher Training University, attracted the attention of
U.S. intelligence agents who helped him travel to the U.S..
</P>
<P>
So far, Mohsen has not personally made any comment on his
son's issue. 
</P>
