<HEADLINE> Khatami Appeals for Tolerance Among Factions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Mohammad Khatami
has urged all factions in the country to exercise tolerance in
order to ensure social stability, the officials news agency IRNA
reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Khatami issued the call during a Saturday speech to religious
figures in Shahr Kord, the southwestern province of
Chaharmahal-Bakhtiari, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami said that the existing differences in the society is a
natural phenomenon, and the way to strengthen and defend religion
is to protect the freedom given by the religion and people's
right to criticize.
</P>
<P>
The moderate leader, arriving in Shahr Kord Saturday afternoon
for a two-day inspection tour, said that criticizing the
president, the Majlis (Parliament), the judiciary and other
officials was allowed, although it must be restricted within the
rule of law.
</P>
<P>
To ensure social stability, all should respect the law and all
three branches of the government should act within the framework
of rules and regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Khatami's remarks came at a time when the country is facing a
heated struggle between the moderate and conservative camps due
to their different views about the country's problems.
</P>
<P>
The moderates advocate political progress in the country,
while the conservatives believe that social crimes and economic
problems are the main issues facing the government.
</P>
<P>
In another meeting with Iranian national football team on
Saturday, Khatami said the Iranian nation should adopt the rule of
football match, in which the two sides compete with each other
without real animosity.
</P>
<P>
"We must learn that human beings have differences of
opinion," he said, "at the same time we must learn to hold
talks with each other."
</P>
<P>
The president expressed regret that the Iranian people have not
yet established a desirable system "for unfortunately we are not
tolerant." He promised that his government would make more efforts
to heal the social division. 
</P>
</TEXT>
