<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Airport Night Move to Go Ahead </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The dramatic overnight move of
airport operations from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok will go ahead as
planned late Sunday despite forecast for heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
Crowds of people flooded to Kai Tak Sunday to catch a last
glimpse of the 73-year-old airport that will be closed Monday.
</P>
<P>
Rain and thunderstorms, as forecast by the Hong Kong
Observatory Sunday morning, will not affect the relocation,
scheduled to start at 5:30 p.m. Sunday and end at 6:30 a.m.
Monday, when the first flight is to land at the new airport,
according to the latest report by the Airport Authority (AA).
</P>
<P>
During the 13 hours, Hong Kong will move all equipment and
facilities from Kai Tak, the world's third busiest international
passenger airport and busiest international cargo airport some 30
km to the west -- the most critical stage of a five-phase
relocation exercise that lasts three months.
</P>
<P>
The night move may be the biggest peace-time operation, which
is composed of some 1,100 vehicle movements by land, sea and air.
</P>
<P>
Starting from Kai Tak near the Kowloon Bay, about 1,000
vehicles will pass through some of the most densely populated
areas anywhere, cross one of the world's longest suspension
bridges, and move westwards to the new airport built on a
reclaimed island 25 km away from the central business district on
Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen convoys are planned, and all will travel under police
escort along the designated routes, and 1,000 policemen will be
deployed to control the traffic.
</P>
<P>
Some large, strange-shaped, utilitarian vehicles familiar on
airport parking areas, such as deck loaders, tractors, pallet
pushers and assorted dollies, will be seen on roads.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 14 barges will sail through Victoria Harbor to
ship heavier loads to Chek Lap Kok, to where 31 airliners will
make a hop from Kai Tak, believed to be the shortest distance they
have ever fly.
</P>
<P>
The heaviest item to be moved will be an aircraft recovery
vehicle, which is big enough to haul a disabled Boeing 747 from
the runway, and the smallest items probably will be 70,000 sets of
utensils that are on the transfer list of Cathay Pacific Catering
Services.
</P>
<P>
Everything has been planned to the finest detail to make a
seamless transfer and ensure that Hong Kong, at all times, has a
fully functional airport, whether Kai Tak or Chek Lap Kok,
according to the AA, which is responsible for building and
management of the new airport.
</P>
<P>
The night move comprises three interlinked operations --
departure from Kai Tak, journey from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok, and
reception and distribution at Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
Each individual vehicle has an allocated time slot to load,
depart and arrive at Chek Lap Kok. The AA will be logging each
vehicle move by computer so that a real-time picture emerges on
how the relocation is proceeding.
</P>
<P>
A dozen government departments and 65 airlines or
aviation-related businesses will take part in the overnight
relocation.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Henry Townsend, AA's Chief Executive Officer, is optimistic
about the relocation, saying that "we don't anticipate any major
problems".
</P>
<P>
"People will probably collapse from exhaustion, and my role is
to help every one and keep an eye on what is going on in the event
of some crises and emergency," said Townsend, who will stay at his
office at Chek Lap Kok throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong Police urge the public time and again to stay home on
the night so that the roads are clear of traffic.
</P>
<P>
At the heel of the overnight relocation, a month-long move will
follow to wrap up the entire process that started on May 6 and
will conclude on August 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
