<HEADLINE> Helicopter Collision Kills 3 in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Three officers of the Philippine Air
Force (PAF) were killed, and three others were injured when two
PAF helicopters collided in mid-air in Zamboanga city, the
Southern Philippines, Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
The official Philippine News Agency quoted Lt. Col. Fredesvindo
Covarrubias, spokesman for the Third Air Division, as confirming
that the ill-fated M6-520 and 510-511 attack helicopters hit each
other shortly after taking off from the Edwin Andrews Airbase in
the city.
</P>
<P>
They were on their way to Cotabato city when the air mishap
occurred around 10:00 (02:00 GMT), he said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman identified the fatalities as Capt. Raymond
Hudador, Lt. Ericzon Ko and Lt. Mario Laphana.
</P>
<P>
He said that the three others, whose identities were not
available, survived the accident with minor injuries.
</P>
<P>
He said a thorough investigation will be conducted by air force
officials to determine the actual cause of the collision.
</P>
<P>
According to Covarrubias, the two helicopters fell some 500
meters apart from each other, one hitting a mango tree near a
river bank while the other fell at the backyard of a house along
Cabato road of the city.
</P>
<P>
No body on the ground was killed or injured, but both
helicopters were irreparably damaged, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
