<HEADLINE> Basic Facts About Hong Kong New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Following are basic facts about
the new Hong Kong International Airport at Chek Lap Kok which
opens Monday for commercial operations:
</P>
<P>
-- The Airport Core Program, covering the new airport and nine
other related infrastructure projects, is the largest
infrastructure development ever undertaken in Hong Kong, and also
ranks among the world's largest infrastructure projects. The
program cost a total of 155.3 billion HK dollars (19.9 billion
U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
-- The new airport is one of the world's most impressive
"fast-track" infrastructure projects, with less than nine years
between the announcement of the construction plan in October 1989
and airport operation in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
-- The Chek Lap Kok site preparation project was the largest
carried out over a short period of time. The 1,248-hectare
airport platform was completed in 31 months, comprising 938
hectares of reclaimed land and 310 hectares from leveling the two
original islands of Chek Lap Kok and Lam Chau.
</P>
<P>
-- The new airport is the only airport in the world to have
every gate, terminal and remote, capable of taking a 747 aircraft
or larger. Its aviation fuel hydrant system can serve aircraft of
any size.
</P>
<P>
-- The second runway, due for completion by the end of 1998,
has a category IIIA rating, the highest safety grade.
</P>
<P>
-- Covering an area of 515,000 square meters upon opening, the
1.3-kilometer-long passenger terminal complex is the world's
largest airport terminal and indoor public place.
</P>
<P>
-- The airport has one of the world's largest flight kitchens,
capable of providing 80,000 flight meals per day. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
