<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Hong Kong New Airport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Hong Kong, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Following are the major events in
the development of the new Hong Kong International Airport at Chek
Lap Kok in a chronological order:
</P>
<P>
Oct. 11, 1989 The plan to construct a new airport at Chek Lap
Kok was announced by the then Governor of Hong Kong, David Wilson,
as part of an overall port and airport development strategy.
</P>
<P>
Sept. 3, 1991 The Memorandum of Understanding was signed by
the Chinese and British governments, who gave their firm support
to the airport project and the rest of the Airport Core Program.
</P>
<P>
Nov. 30, 1992 Award of the 9.04 billion HK dollar (1.16
billion U.S. dollar) site preparation contract which encompassed
the formation of the 1,248-hectare platform at Chek Lap Kok on
which the new airport was to be constructed. This was the second
largest contract awarded for the new airport development.
</P>
<P>
Nov. 4, 1994 The Airport Committee of the Sino-British Liaison
Group signed the Agreed Minute on the financing of Hong Kong's new
airport and airport railway.
</P>
<P>
Jan. 28, 1995 Award of the 10.1 billion HK dollar (1.29
billion U.S. dollar) contract for the passenger terminal building
structure. This was the largest contract awarded for the entire
Airport Core Program.
</P>
<P>
Apr. 25, 1995 Award of the 2.61 billion HK dollar (334 million
U.S. dollar) airfield works contract which included the
construction of the first (southern) runway, taxi way and aprons.
</P>
<P>
Jun. 16, 1995 Completion of the reclamation and excavation to
create the 1,248-hectare airport platform.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 1, 1995 The Airport Authority Ordinance came into effect,
and the Airport Authority (AA), a statutory body responsible for
designing, construction, and management of the new airport, held
its first board meeting.
</P>
<P>
Dec. 15, 1995 Award of the contract for the transportation
center which would contain the station for airport railway and
other public transport facilities.
</P>
<P>
Jan. 1996 Planning works on the various issues related to the
transition of the airport operations from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok
commenced.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 1996 Completion of the new airport Air Traffic Control
Complex and Tower, located in the midfield area between the
parallel runways.
</P>
<P>
May 6, 1996 AA signed an agreement with Cathay Pacific Airways
to develop a 3.5-billion-HK dollar (450 million U.S. dollar)
headquarters on 3.3 hectares of land. The complex covered 90,000
square meters, with a ten-story office block, a 23-story crew
accommodation block and other facilities.
</P>
<P>
May 30, 1996 The Airport Committee of the Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group signed an agreement to allow early development of a
second (northern) runway and associated facilities at the new
airport.
</P>
<P>
Feb. 20, 1997 A twin engine Government Flying Service aircraft
made first landing on the southern runway at the new airport at
Chek Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
Apr. 30, 1997 Award of northern runway works contract.
</P>
<P>
Aug. 7, 1997 AA signed an agreement with Hong Kong Dragon
Airlines Limited and China National Aviation Corporation (Group)
Limited to develop a 32,500-square-meter building at the new
airport.
</P>
<P>
Nov. 15, 1997 A replica of the first aircraft that flew in
Hong Kong made a commemorative flight over the new airport at Chek
Lap Kok.
</P>
<P>
Jan. 13, 1998 The Hong Kong Special Administrative Region
government announced that the new airport would open for
commercial operation on July 6, 1998 and would be named Hong Kong
International Airport.
</P>
<P>
May 6, 1998 The first phase of relocation of airport
operations from Kai Tak to Chek Lap Kok started, and the whole
process, divided into five phases, would last for three months.
</P>
<P>
Jun. 14, 1998 The last trial operation of the new airport took
place, involving 15,000 people and three aircraft landings. It was
the largest and most integrated trial operation of airfield,
passenger terminal and airport railway links.
</P>
<P>
Jul. 2, 1998 Chinese President Jiang Zemin officiated at the
opening ceremony of the new airport, and his plane was the first
commercial aircraft to take off from the airport. Eight hours
later, U.S. President Bill Clinton's plane touched down, becoming
the first aircraft to land at the airport.
</P>
<P>
Jul. 5, 1998 A dramatic overnight move from Kai Tak to Chek
Lap Kok, which includes more than 10,000 movements by road, sea,
and air within 13 hours between 5:30 p.m. on July 5 and 6:30 a.m.
on July 6.
</P>
<P>
Jul. 6, 1998 The Hong Kong International Airport at Chek Lap
Kok opens for commercial aviation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
