<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten-Project Airport Core Program (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The opening of Hong Kong's new
airport at Chek Lap Kok marks the successful conclusion of the
10-project 155.3-billion-HK-dollar (19.9 billion U.S. dollars)
Airport Core Program, which is the largest infrastructure
development undertaken in Hong Kong.

1. New Airport
</P>
<P>
The new airport at Chek Lap Kok is almost four times the size
of existing airport at Kai Tak. The "greenfield" site was formed
by leveling the tiny islands of Chek Lap Kok and Lam Chau and
reclaiming land from the sea.
</P>
<P>
On opening, with the first of its two 3,800-meter runways in
service, the new airport will be able to handle 35 million
passengers and three million tons of air cargo a year, compared
with the 28.3 million passengers and 1.79 million tons of cargo
passing through Kai Tak in 1997. The new airport will operate
round the clock without the night-time flight restrictions imposed
at the Kai Tak airport.
</P>
<P>
The new airport will be developed in phases and ultimately is
expected to handle 87 million passengers and nine million tons of
air cargo annually.
</P>
<P>
The passenger terminal building is very spacious. It will
eventually have a gross floor area of nearly 550,000 square
meters, or nine times as large as that of Kai Tak, with 30,000
square meters dedicated to retailing. Sign posting in English and
Chinese throughout the terminal will be clear and simple.
</P>
<P>
There will be 38 bridge-served gates for wide-bodied aircraft
(48 by the end of 1998 after extension of the northwest
concourse). Accessibility to the gates will be facilitated by a
driverless shuttle train and moving walkways.
</P>
<P>
Departing passengers should take less than three minutes to
check in at nearly 300 desks. From each of these desks, as well as
16 over-sized baggage check-in counters, luggage will move
smoothly on its way through a sophisticated baggage handling and
screening system, so the highest levels of security will be
maintained. It should take no more than 30 minutes to complete
check-in and immigration formalities to board aircraft.
</P>
<P>
With 12 reclaim carousels handling almost 20,000 pieces of
luggage an hour, passengers will be able to retrieve their baggage
quickly after entering the arrivals area.

2. The Airport Railway
</P>
<P>
The Airport Railway, 34 kilometers long, is the world's first
railway built specifically to serve an airport. It has two
separate services: the Airport Express and the domestic service --
the Tung Chung Line, with the trains running at speeds up to 135
kilometers per hour.
</P>
<P>
The Airport Express, designed as an all-seated, business
class-type service, carries passengers between the new airport and
the Central District of Hong Kong Island in just 23 minutes.
There are two intermediate stops at Kowloon and Tsing Yi.
</P>
<P>
In-town check-in facilities will be provided at the Hong Kong
and Kowloon stations, and baggage checked in will be carried in a
separate car.
</P>
<P>
The Tung Chung Line, providing a mass transit-type service
between Hong Kong Island and Tung Chung new town, has intermediate
stations at Kowloon, Tai Kok Tsui (Olympic Station), Lai King (an
interchange with the existing MTR Tsuen Wan Line) and Tsing Yi.
This service, designed to carry more than 260,000 passengers
daily, can ease congestion on the present Mass Transit Railway
(MTR) Tsuen Wan line.

3. New Town
</P>
<P>
The new town has been built on specially reclaimed land at Tung
Chung, Lantau Island, as a support community for the new airport.
</P>
<P>
It is not only the latest new town in Hong Kong, but also the
first new town located on an outlying island. It has been designed
to blend in with its rural surroundings.
</P>
<P>
Under Phase 1 development, the new town has a population of
20,000, with up to 15,000 living in public housing. About 10,000
residents have moved into the new town.
</P>
<P>
Further stages of development, greatly expanding the new town's
area, will provide for a population of about 200,000 by the year
2011.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ten-Project Airport Core Program in HK (2) 4. The Lantau Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Lantau Link, opened to traffic on May 22, 1997, has become
a new landmark in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
It is the vital link in the transport network serving the new
airport, comprising the Tsing Ma Bridge, the Kap Shui Mun Bridge
and a connecting Ma Wan Viaduct.
</P>
<P>
Throughout its 3.5 kilometer length, the double-decked Lantau
Link has a similar configuration: six road lanes on the open upper
deck and two road lanes for use in bad weather, or in emergency,
on the sheltered lower deck, which will also carry the airport
railway.
</P>
<P>
The Tsing Ma Bridge is the world's longest span suspension
bridge carrying both road and rail traffic. Its main span of 1,377
meters is more than twice the length of the Sydney Harbor Bridge
which is 500 meters long and 97 meters longer than San Francisco's
Golden Gate Bridge.
</P>
<P>
The Tsing Ma Bridge has been designed to withstand typhoons
with wind speeds of up to 342 kilometers per hour. The highest
gust wind speed ever recorded in Hong Kong is 259 kilometers per
hour in 1962.
</P>
<P>
The Kap Shui Mun Bridge, though smaller than its sister bridge
Tsing Ma, is the world's longest cable-stayed bridge to carry both
road and rail traffic.

5. Western Harbor Crossing
</P>
<P>
The two-kilometer Western Harbor Crossing, opened to traffic on
April 30, 1997, is the third road tunnel built under Victoria
Harbor. It runs from the reclaimed land at West Kowloon to Sai
Ying Pun on Hong Kong Island.
</P>
<P>
The six-lane tunnel has a maximum capacity of 180,000 vehicles
daily, far exceeding that of the existing four-lane tunnels.
</P>
<P>
Its 1.36-kilometer immersed tube section comprises 12 concrete
units each weighing 35,000 tons.

6. North Lantau Expressway
</P>
<P>
The North Lantau Expressway was opened to traffic on May 22,
1997.
</P>
<P>
The 12.5-kilometer expressway runs along the north Lantau
coast, from the Lantau Link to the new airport. It is the first
highway constructed along the island's northern coastline.
</P>
<P>
More than half the route is on reclaimed land.
</P>
<P>
An interchange at Tung Chung will provide direct access to the
new town.

7. Route 3 (part)
</P>
<P>
Two sections of this north-south route are built as part of the
Airport Core Program -- the Tsing Yi and Kwai Chung sections.
</P>
<P>
Tsing Yi section comprises a 1.6-kilometer dual three-lane
twin-tube tunnel through Tsing Yi Island and a 500-meter bridge
over the Rambler Channel that separates the island from the
mainland. It was opened to traffic on May 22, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Kwai Chung section is a viaduct built 20 meters above ground.
Unlike the rest of the road transport network, it has eight lanes.
The three-kilometer viaduct was opened to the public on February
20, 1997. It links the Rambler Channel Bridge in the north and the
West Kowloon Expressway in the south.

8. West Kowloon Expressway
</P>
<P>
The West Kowloon Expressway, opened to traffic on February 20,
1997,  is a four-kilometer expressway running from the Kwai Chung
viaduct to the Western Harbor Crossing toll plaza.
</P>
<P>
The northern section is carried on a viaduct and the southern
section is at ground level.
</P>
<P>
Two interchanges provide for connections with the local
transport network.

9. West Kowloon Reclamation
</P>
<P>
The West Kowloon Reclamation is the largest reclamation project
ever undertaken in the urban area -- increasing the size of the
Kowloon peninsula by one-third and extending the waterfront into
the harbor by as much as one kilometer.
</P>
<P>
The project provides 334 hectares of new land between Yau Ma
Tei and Lai Chi Kok. This land is being used for the transport
infrastructure serving the new airport. It will also be used for
various other purposes, including public and private housing for
over 90,000 people, government and community facilities and
recreational areas.

10. Central Reclamation (phase 1)
</P>
<P>
Twenty hectares of land have been reclaimed from the Central
waterfront and a further six hectares of existing land are being
redeveloped.
</P>
<P>
The reclamation, between Rumsey Street and Pedder Street, has
extended the waterfront by up to 350 meters beyond Central's
existing shoreline.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong terminus of the Airport Railway is built on the
new land, which also provides opportunities for the expansion of
the Central business district.
</P>
<P>
Four new ferry piers, serving both inner harbor and outlying
inland routes, have been opened on the reclaimed land. A large
promenade has been provided as well as a bus terminus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
