<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Hails Jiang's Central Asian Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The successful visit by Chinese
President Jiang Zemin to the Central Asian nation of Kazakhstan
represents another major contribution to regional peace and
development, China's People's Daily said in an editorial Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Jiang, in his visit Friday through Saturday, first attended a
meeting with the leaders of Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Russia and
Tajikistan. High on the agenda of the five-nation meeting was
regional peace and stability as well as multilateral economic
cooperation. At the one-day meeting, the leaders reached consensus
on the following points:
</P>
<P>
-- They will continue to observe the universally-accepted norms
governing international relations: mutual respect for sovereignty
and territory integrity, equality and mutual benefit, and
non-interference in each other's internal affairs;
</P>
<P>
-- They will solve the differences and disputes between their
countries through friendly consultations;
</P>
<P>
-- They will join efforts in fighting against various forms of
public evils, such as national splittism, religious extremism,
terrorism, arms smuggling and drug trafficking;
</P>
<P>
-- They will forge closer economic ties in pursuit of mutual
benefit;
</P>
<P>
-- They will work with the world community to prevent a nuclear
arms race in South Asia and safeguard the international nuclear
non-proliferation regime.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese president reiterated that China favors a
comprehensive ban and total destruction of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
He said that unconditionally, China will never be the first to
use nuclear weapons; that under no circumstances will China ever
use, or threaten to use, nuclear weapons against any nuclear-free
country or nuclear-free zone, and that China has no intention to
resume nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
The editorial noted that China's cooperation with the four
countries is a clear demonstration that China has always been a
major force to promote world peace and development, and that its
development and strength will bring greater security and more
chances of cooperation, instead of any threat, to the world.
</P>
<P>
On bilateral relations with Kazakhstan, the editorial noted
that President Jiang's visit is also an important event, because
the leaders of the two countries have re-designed a new blueprint
for bilateral relations in the next century.
</P>
<P>
In particular, the supplementary border agreement signed during
the visit is the third legal document of this nature and marks a
complete settlement of all the issues concerning the
1,700-kilometer-long border between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
This will not only help deepen their mutual trust and
friendship but also have a positive impact on their efforts to
solve similar issues with their other neighbors, the editorial
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
