<HEADLINE> Yugoslavia Marks Anniversary of Anti-Fascist Uprising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Mass rallies were held in major
cities across Yugoslavia on Saturday to mark the 57th anniversary
of the country's anti-fascist uprising.
</P>
<P>
On July 4, 1941, the then Communist Party of Yugoslavia decided
to stage an armed uprising against the invasion of German and
Italian forces, which triggered off the country's four-year
anti-fascist war.
</P>
<P>
At a mass rally held in Prijepolje in west Serbia, Bozidar
Jovanovic, a war veteran, said that for both Yugoslavia and
Europe, the 1941 uprising is of both great historic and profound
practical significance.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the currently tense situation in the troubled
Yugoslav province of Kosovo, Jovanovic said that every citizen of
the Federation of Yugoslavia has a duty to safeguard the
federation's independence and territorial integrity.
</P>
<P>
He also warned certain western forces against supporting
separatism and terrorism in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
The World War II veterans taking part in the rally sent a
message to Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, offering full
support to the president's efforts to safeguard the country and to
seek a peaceful end to the Kosovo crisis through political
dialogue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
