<HEADLINE> Zambia to Take Steps to Protect Local Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick Chiluba
has said that his government is to sign trade agreements with
neighboring countries to protect local industries threatened by
imported subsidized goods.
</P>
<P>
Opening the one-week 34th Zambia international trade fair
Saturday in Ndola, 330 kilometers north of Lusaka, Chiluba said
it is imperative to sign such agreements because some foreign
companies have capitalized on Zambia's liberalized economy to
dump goods on the local market, Zambia Daily Mail reported
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The liberalization of our economy had at times brought in
undesired international companies who have seized the opportunity
to dump goods on our market," said the president.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the trade agreements are intended to bring the
country's manufacturing industry on the line of fair competition
with other firms in the region.
</P>
<P>
However, Chiluba explained that the measures in the trade
agreements are not intended to stop the economic integration
process in the eastern and southern Africa but to compliment the
regional cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He said to ensure the playing field is leveled, it is the
government's duty to promote a tax system that is responsive to
the business growth.
</P>
<P>
Zambia needs a tax system which does not encourage loopholes
for cheating and evasion, said the president, adding that the
Zambia Revenue Authority will have to constantly work with the
business community to sustain development.
</P>
<P>
The annual international trade fair whose theme is "Trade
Without Borders" has attracted 154 local companies and 99 firms
from nine foreign countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
