<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Bangladesh Devalues Currency to Boost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladesh Bank Sunday devalued
the country's currency taka by 1.7 percent against the U.S. dollar
in an attempt to boost export and increase its foreign exchange
reserve.
</P>
<P>
This is the second downward adjustment of the taka this year
and the 13th since the Awami League-led government was formed in
June 1996.
</P>
<P>
The bank's buying and selling rates for the U.S. dollar now
stand at 46.95 and 47.25 taka per dollar as against 46.15 taka and
46.45 taka respectively before the devaluation which, according to
the country's central bank, the Bangladesh Bank, was aimed at
"maintaining incentives for exports and for inflow from expatriate
Bangladeshis."
</P>
<P>
Financial analysts are concerned whether devaluation, the
"prescribed medicine" for supporting exports, could reach the
desired results.
</P>
<P>
In early February this year, the taka was devalued in the wake
of widespread currency depreciation in Southeast Asia, in the hope
that the move would help improve the competitiveness of
Bangladesh's exports and raise its foreign exchange reserve.
</P>
<P>
But the foreign exchange reserve did not demonstrate a strong
upward trend as expected, which rose slightly to 1.68 billion
dollars as of June 1 from 1.67 billion on January 8, while export
earnings which stood at about 4.1 billion dollars during the first
10 months of the past fiscal year ending on June 30, were 10
million dollars short of the target.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation this time is the result of pressure from
exporters and the business community as a whole to accelerate
exports, particularly ready-made garments, after the depreciation
in the value of Indian and Pakistani rupee under economic
sanctions following their nuclear tests in May, press reports here
said.
</P>
<P>
While devaluation promotes exports, encourages remittances of
foreign currency by Bangladeshi workers abroad and hence may
increase the country's foreign exchange reserve, it also
discourages imports causing a fall in the government's revenue
earnings. And with procurements from other countries becoming
costlier, the supply prices shot up, possibly inducing high
inflation into the economy, exerts said.
</P>
<P>
Since most of Bangladeshi industries, especially its no. 1
foreign exchange earner the garment industry, are heavily
dependent on imported raw materials, it will not be easy to
squeeze anything significant from a situation where the import
costs will go up, they said.
</P>
<P>
And if investors do not feel confident, the country's export
base will be wakened, they added.
</P>
<P>
Exports can be spurred through increasing operational
efficiency and measures like tax exemption or rebate for the
benefit of exporters, according to the analysts.
</P>
<P>
The devaluation might give an impetus to export and help
increase the country's foreign exchange reserve to some extent,
but it would have an adverse effect on the country's industrial
investment in the long run, considering that it would curb the
country's imports and affecting its revenue earnings, they pointed
out. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
