<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panama Declines Bargain With U.S. on Military Bases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 4 (Xinhua) -- The Panamanian government on
Saturday ruled out the possibility that it would negotiate with
the United States the continuing presence of U.S. troops in the
central American country after their mission expires in 2000.
</P>
<P>
"There is no possibility of re-negotiating the military bases
with the United States, as suggested by U.S. Senator Jesse Helms,
in case the Multinational Drug Center project is aborted," said
Panamanian Minister of State for Canal Affairs Jorge Ritter.
</P>
<P>
Ritter, also the key negotiator for the drug center project,
known as CMA in Spanish, said Panamanian President Ernesto Perez
Balladares made it clear that there would be no re-negotiation on
the issue whether the United States asked for it or not.
</P>
<P>
Under the 1977 Canal Treaty signed between Panama and the
United States, the latter should withdraw completely its troops
from Panamanian territories on the last day of 1999.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, President Balladares initiated the CMA project. The
planned anti-drug facility, in which several Latin American
nations have been invited, is conceived as a civilian program but
will include a U.S. military component yet to be clearly defined.
</P>
<P>
The two countries reached at the end of last year an accord in
principle on the possible establishment of the CMA through
negotiations to be held during the following two years.
</P>
<P>
Panama presented to the United States a new proposal on the
issue and is now awaiting the U.S. government's response.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. final answer on the CMA is expected to come next week,
after the long holiday Washington will have to celebrate the
country's Independence Day, which falls on July 4.
</P>
<P>
Reports from Washington said U.S. Senate Foreign Relations
Committee Chairman Jesse Helms and House of Representatives
International Relations Committee Chairman Benjamin Gilman will
ask President Bill Clinton to renegotiate the bases issue in case
of a possible failure in the CMA negotiations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
