<HEADLINE> Thailand's Car Output Plunges Considerably </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Car production in Thailand dropped
by 76.9 percent in the first five months of this year as a result
of the economic recession, the Federation of Thai Industries said
in a statement received Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The statement said car assemblies between January and May this
year stood at only 49,798 units, compared with the 215,768 units
during the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Motorcycle assembling also went down by 50.8 percent to 269,872
units from 548,783 units during the same period last year, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
It said truck assembly, which accounted for 78 percent of
overall car production, fell by 73.2 percent to 38,839 units,
while passenger car output fell by 85.3 percent to 10,236 units.
</P>
<P>
However, the exports of cars, motorcycles and auto parts surged
sharply over the five months, said the statement.
</P>
<P>
It said exports of cars were up by 71 percent to 20,070 units,
while their value jumped by 138.9 percent in local currency terms
to some 9 billion baht (219 million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
