<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Infrastructure Loans Increasing in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Chinese state banks are expanding
loans to infrastructure construction to stimulate national
economic development.
</P>
<P>
According to a China Daily report, China will invest a total of
1,100 billion US dollars in its massive infrastructure
construction program, including the building of new railways,
highways and urban public utilities within three years.
</P>
<P>
Bank loans, one of the major funding sources, will pay a key
role in facilitating the infrastructure construction projects, the
paper said.
</P>
<P>
Some state banks have adjusted their loan structures to offer
more lending to infrastructure construction, simplified the
procedures of loan assessment and even extended loans in advance
to projects where repayment is guaranteed.
</P>
<P>
These banks have also raised the loan ratios of their head
offices to provide direct funding to key state projects.
</P>
<P>
"This measure will meet the financial demands of important
state projects in the infrastructure and technological renovation
sectors," said a bank official.
</P>
<P>
Led by the central bank, China's banking circle has also set up
a system where bank representatives meet to timely declare
information on their banks' lending to infrastructure construction
projects and discuss solutions to existing problems.
</P>
<P>
The State Development Bank had granted 16.35 billion yuan (1.96
billion US dollars) in loans to railway construction by the end of
May, completing its annual loan plan for the rail sector. China
Construction Bank offered six billion yuan (722 million US
dollars) to rail projects by May, accounting for 85 percent of its
yearly target.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China, the Agricultural
Bank of China and the China Construction Bank are assessing 140
loan projects valued at 57.9 billion yuan (6.98 billion US
dollars) in road construction.
</P>
<P>
While actively supporting infrastructure construction, these
banks have also been careful to avoid financial risks by
intensifying loan management and making sure that injected loans
are strictly in line with lending regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
