<HEADLINE> Equities Fail to Sustain Initial Rally on BSE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Equities failed to sustain the
initial sharp rally and once again showed substantial falls on the
Bombay Stock Exchange (BSE) market during the week as the negative
political developments weighed heavily on the sentiment.
</P>
<P>
The BSE sensitive index, which spurted to 3,289.56 points
Monday, later moved down gradually to end the week at 3,089.02 as
against last weekend's close of 3,168.82, netting a loss of 79.80
points.
</P>
<P>
The national index also dropped by 36.12 points to close the
week at 1,355.70 from last weekend close of 1391.82. The BSE-200
and us dollar index were quoted down at 300.01 and 121.08 points
compared with last weekend close of 317.52 and 123.78
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The early upsurge on the market was halted as operators
withdrew from the market in view of prevailing restrictions on
trading and selling pressure from foreign institutional investors.
</P>
<P>
The major factors for players turning cautious were the United
States attack on Iraqi missile site giving rise to speculation
about a likely war, followed by changing unstable political
situation in the country.  
