<HEADLINE> Chinese Group Wins Thai Bridge Building Contract </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese joint venture has been
awarded a contract to build Rama VIII Bridge across the Chao
Phraya River running through Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The group, made up of China State Construction Engineering
Corp., PPD Construction Co. and BBR System Ltd.-PCD Group
Engineering Consultant Co., won the contract to build the
2.45-kilometer Rama VIII Bridge for 2.88 billion baht (702 million
U.S. dollars), Sunday's Bangkok Post reported.
</P>
<P>
That is 142 million baht (3.5 million dollars) less than the
price quote of its only rival, a foreign company.
</P>
<P>
The paper said price was the sole determining factor as the two
shortlisted rivals have passed technical screening.
</P>
<P>
Bangkok required 3 billion baht (731 million dollars) in bank
guarantees from the company to make sure that the construction
work would run smoothly and that work would not come to a halt due
to financial problems later.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese consortium would have access to the land to begin
construction within a few months after the city pays land
expropriation fee to 300 families of landowners in the
construction area.
</P>
<P>
The project is scheduled for completion by the end of 2000.
</P>
