<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Cooperatives' Role in Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's cooperative sector has
been playing a role in changing the country's socio-economic life
under the market-oriented economic system, partly contributing to
its economic development.
</P>
<P>
The country has established more than 21,700 cooperative
societies with 2.8 million members, Myanmar Minister of
Cooperatives U Aung San was quoted by Sunday's The New Light of
Myanmar as saying.
</P>
<P>
Marking the International Day of Cooperatives here Saturday,
the minister said Myanmar has also set up agricultural and
industrial producers' cooperative societies, and 30 agricultural
special regions.
</P>
<P>
After the formation of the Cooperative Export-Import
Enterprise, the export value of the organization reached 20.4
million U.S. dollars up to March this year, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
According to a report on Myanmar's financial, economic and
social conditions, the country's cooperative sector contributed
2.1 percent to the gross domestic product (GDP) in the 1997-98
fiscal year ending March.
</P>
<P>
In the three main goods sectors which contributed most to the
GDP in the year, the cooperative enterprises also shared 2.1
percent in its output value in agriculture, 1.4 percent in meat
and fish, and 0.9 percent in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
The cooperatives took up 1.3 percent in services value in
transport sector while making up 2.3 percent in volume in the
trade sector.
</P>
<P>
The report added that cooperative-owned factories exceeded 630
out of 51,738 in the country.
</P>
<P>
The International Day of Cooperatives is observed on the first
</P>
<P>
Saturday of July beginning 1995 according to a resolution of the
United Nations General Assembly in December 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
