<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Working on New Pension System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government faces many
challenges in establishing a multiple pillar pension system, which
is in preparation for an aging generation in the 21st Century,
today's China daily reported.
</P>
<P>
China is planning to establish a comprehensive pension system,
characterized by multiple channels of funding sources, multiple
levels of insurance means and a combination of social pooling and
individual accounts, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The government initiated a major campaign to overhaul the
country's pension system last year, issuing a newly-defined
regulation for the old age pension system for enterprise employees.
</P>
<P>
"These initiatives, focusing on the transformation from the
defined-benefit and pay-as-you-go system to a multiple pillar
social security network, are encouraging," the paper quoted
Srinivasa Madhur, a senior economist with the Asian Development
Bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
"However, the movement towards a multiple pillar pension
system, using individual funding accounts for pension recipients,
poses problems relating to financing the transition," Madhur
noted.
</P>
<P>
China needs to establish a comprehensive regulatory framework
for social security, including the prudential regulation of
pension funds, the disclosure of information and the supervision
of the pension funds, Madhur said, adding that extending the
coverage of the pension system is also necessary.
</P>
<P>
Due to the one-child policy introduced in the second half of the
1970s and increasing life expectancy, China's population is aging
rapidly, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
At present, people aged 60 and above account for about nine
percent of China's 1.24 billion population, this figure, is
predicted to expand by 13 percent by 2030, according to the China
population Society.
</P>
<P>
"with an aging population, the financial resources needed for
providing for an old-age social security will grow enormously at
that time," said Yan Kun, an economist with the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is more compelling since the current pension system
is not yet workable,' he added.
</P>
<P>
China's current pension system is characterized by a social
welfare and pay-as-you-go types, covering mainly the state-owned
enterprises, government employees and military personnel. Although
a pension scheme was introduced for farmers on an experimental
basis in 1996, it has only scarce coverage in rural areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
