<HEADLINE> 20 Billion Dollars Invested in Brazil's Auto Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's auto industry in
the past four years has received cash injection worth about 20
billion U.S. dollars, said a press here Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Seventeen foreign automakers, including 11 newcomers, have
announced their plans to build new factories in Brazil, said the
Brazilian Association of Motor Vehicle Manufacturers (Anfavea).
</P>
<P>
The capital inflow into the auto industry is after a stable
Brazilian currency and the government's favorable industrial
policy, said Celio Batalha, vice president of the Anfavea.
</P>
<P>
Another reason behind the increased funding, Batalha was quoted
as saying, is that foreign investors are assured of the bright
prospects of the Brazil market, particularly in the auto sector.
</P>
<P>
Brazil's auto industry registered a 36 percent growth from 1994
through 1997, with sales up from 1.206 million units to 1.64
million.
</P>
<P>
Industry analysts said the nation's auto production would reach
3 million units by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
