<HEADLINE> ASEAN Officials Discuss Regional Currency Crisis in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Senior finance officials of the nine
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
are meeting here to discuss the regional currency crisis which has
been sweeping the region for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
The two-day third meeting of the ASEAN finance officials, which
began Saturday, is the first regional meeting on the sector held
in Myanmar which joined ASEAN in last July.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar Minister of Finance and Revenue U Khin Maung Thein said
at the meeting that the crisis affected his country slightly,
adding that Myanmar will participate in resolving the crisis in
cooperation with other ASEAN member countries.
</P>
<P>
He thanked the Asian Development Bank (ADB) and Japan for their
assistance extended to Myanmar.
</P>
<P>
He stressed continued cooperation in tasks on ASEAN and its
objectives while implementing all economic projects including
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Last December, Myanmar and other member countries signed a
memorandum of understanding on multilateral cooperation in ASEAN's
financial sector at a special meeting of the grouping's finance
ministers held in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
In February this year, Myanmar reaffirmed at the second ASEAN
finance ministers' meeting its readiness to cooperate with other
member countries in resolving the currency and other economic
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Attending the meeting are also Myanmar ambassadors to ASEAN and
Japan, and representatives of the ADB.
</P>
<P>
Senior finance officials of ASEAN and Japan will also meet to
discuss their cooperation.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia, Myanmar,
the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
</TEXT>
