<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Sexual Harassment Law Is Needed: Chinese Lawmakers (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wang Hong, a 30-year-old female employee of a government agency
in Beijing, says that instances of women being harassed in
hospital or during a regular physical examination at work units
are quite common.
</P>
<P>
Women have begun to wake up to the importance of
self-protection, but it is very difficult to bring the crime
before a court because there is often no witness, or insufficient
evidence, or no way to tell whether it is harassment or not, Wang
explains and adds, "I think it is necessary to pass a law to
punish those who commit such crimes in order to protect women's
rights and interests."
</P>
<P>
One study of 45 women involved in different jobs in Beijing
found the majority saying that they have not been harassed, but
admitting that they have heard friends complain about sexual
harassment or have read reports in the tabloids. The major media
in China usually keep silent about this.
</P>
<P>
Hu Min, also a member of the NPC Standing Committee and
vice-chairman of the Central Committee of the Revolutionary
Committee of the Chinese Kuomintang, says that he is certain that,
with an improved sense of self-protection, sexual harassment will
be put on Chinese legislators' agenda, even though there is no
precedent to follow in coming up with penalties. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> A Sexual Harassment Law Is Needed: Chinese Lawmakers (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Standing Committee
of China's National People's Congress, Chen Guizun, said today
that the country needs a law on punish sexual harassment and
unfair use of position and power.
</P>
<P>
Chen told the third meeting of the NPC Standing committee last
week that assaulting a woman with obscenities or taking liberties
with the opposite sex by using one's position and power is in fact
a kind of crime and he suggested that a law be passed so that
sexual harassment can be penalized. His suggestion has won the
support of many legislators.
</P>
<P>
Legal scholars say that this is the first time for sexual
harassment to get the attention of legislators. The Chinese have
long been conservative about sexual matters, and people who are
harassed often do not breathe a word of it to anyone, but complain
about it in private, Chen, who was a professor at Beijing's
University of Geology and is now vice-chairman of the Standing
Committee of the Jiangxi Provincial People's Congress, explained.
</P>
<P>
"They have to bear the insult in silence," he said, and this
has had a great impact, although sexual harassment by doctors is
not so common in the country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
