<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Official Responds to Claims on Human Organ Transplants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In May of 1996, the Ministry of Public Health, Ministry of
Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation and the General
Administration of Customs published a regulation banning the use
of human tissue and organs, including fetuses, to produce medical
preparations; prohibiting the trading of human tissue or organs;
and making it illegal to donate or exchange human tissue and
organs with any overseas organizations or individuals.
</P>
<P>
"China does not allow any work unit or individuals to be
involved in handling the bodies of executed convicts or their
organs," said the public health official. "Neither does it allow
the organs of executed convicts to be removed through coercive
means or illicit collecting and trading in human organs."
</P>
<P>
It is illegal to trade in human organs in China, and any
violation will be punished according to law, the official
said. China's Customs officials have never uncovered or
intercepted a single case of human organs being transported out of
China, he said.
</P>
<P>
The health official described as "absolutely groundless" the
accusations at the U.S. House of Representative hearing that China
removes and sells organs from the executed prisoners and "even
removes organs from the convicts on the death roll, or time the
execution to suit the special needs of organ transplants."
</P>
<P>
He said the U.S. House of Representatives should have brought
Harry Wu and the unidentified man to testify at the hearing,
adding that Wu is notorious for making up stories against China.
</P>
<P>
In 1995 Wu produced a TV documentary about surgery in a Chinese
hospital, claiming it was an organ transplant operation using a
kidney from an executed prisoner, the public health official
said. However, the documentary clearly shows the surgery was
carried out on the patient's chest instead of the stomach where a
kidney transplant operation should be, he said.
</P>
<P>
China cleared up the facts and exposed Wu's ill intentions
after the TV documentary was released and shown in some western
countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official said the U.S. House of Representative held the
hearing on the eve of President Clinton's visit to China and then
invited Wu to bear witness.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
