<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria Worried About Fate of Hostages in Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, July 4 (Xinhua) -- Bulgaria is worried about the fate of
three Serbs and a Serbia citizen of Bulgarian origin taken hostage
Thursday by the outlawed Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), a Foreign
Ministry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman, Radko Vlaikov, said that the Bulgarian
government has asked the International Red Cross, the Organization
for Security and Cooperation in Europe and the UN High
Commissioner for Refugees to look into the incident.
</P>
<P>
Among the four kidnapped was Stamen Genov, a 24-year-old ethnic
Bulgarian from Bosilegrad in Serbia. He served as a military
doctor at the hospital of Djacovica, Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the KLA armed men stopped the bus carrying Genov
and the three Serbs near the Crnoevo village and took them hostage.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria's concern is humanitarian, said Vlaikov. "We are
worried about the fate of Dr Genov and the other hostages."
</P>
<P>
He said that the incident once again confirms the necessity for
the international community to be active in seeking a quick and
durable solution to the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
