<DOCNO> XIE19980705.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-07-05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Health Official Responds to Claims on Human Organ Transplants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- A senior official with the Ministry
of Public Health stated here today that human organ transplants in
China are conducted strictly on a voluntary basis and that the
majority of organs for this purpose are donated voluntarily by
citizens or the recipients' relatives.
</P>
<P>
He made the statement to clear up what he called the slanderous
rumors of Harry Wu and an unidentified man at a recent U.S. House
of Representative hearing over organ transplants involving
executed Chinese criminals.
</P>
<P>
As a new field of modern medical science, human organ
transplants represent the cutting edge of advanced medical
technology that plays a big role in saving the lives of patients
in serious conditions, the ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
To advance China's medical scientific research and for
humanitarian purposes, the official said, some Chinese hospitals
and medical research institutes have experimented with human organ
transplant research and clinic practices involving such organs as
livers, kidneys, corneas and skeletons.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1960s, the Chinese government has called for organ
donations from citizens on a voluntary basis. The late Chinese
statesman Deng Xiaoping, for example, stated in his will that his
corneas be denoted after his death, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Some Chinese hospitals and medical research institutes began to
set up human organ banks in the 1980s to receive and keep donated
organs, he said.
</P>
<P>
"It is rare in China to use the bodies of executed convicts or
organs from an executed convict," he said. "If there is any, it is
put under stringent state control and must go through standard
procedures."
</P>
<P>
A document issued jointly by the Supreme People's Court and the
Ministry of Public Health in the 1980s stipulates that hospitals
and medical research institutes can use the remains of the
executed convicts or their organs only with the voluntary
agreement and the signature of the convicts themselves or with the
consent of the convicts' relatives.
</P>
<P>
The use of such organs is limited to humanitarian purposes,
must undergo strict examination and be approved by the health
department and judicial department, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As far as organ donations are concerned, the convicts are
treated equally with other citizens," stressed the health
official.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
