<HEADLINE> Highlights of Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 5 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese president Jiang Zemin wound up his working visit to
Kazakhstan and returned to China yesterday. Jiang set off on July
3 for Alma-Ata of Kazakhstan to attend the five-nation meeting of
China, Kazakhstan, Kyrghyzstan, Russia and Tajikistan. The meeting
mainly discussed such issues as regional security and economic
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Jiang held talks with Kazakhstan President
Nursultan Nazarbayev and the two presidents signed the second
supplement to the Border Demarcation Agreement between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- The water level on China's major rivers -- including the
Yangtze, Huaihe and Nenjiang rivers -- have risen above warning
lines.
</P>
<P>
-- Tian Jiyun, Vice-Chairman of the Standing Committee of the
National People's Congress, yesterday urged the taxation
law-enforcement inspection teams nationwide to seriously and
effectively carry out their work, saying that paying taxes is the
duty of each enterprise and individual.
</P>
<P>
"Beijing Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Jia Qinglin, mayor of Beijing, urged that 67 environmental
protection projects be completed in the Chinese capital to mark
the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's Republic next
year.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- Foreign direct investment in China decreased 6.85 percent
from a year ago to 3.17 billion U.S. dollars in May, indicating
that years of the continued growth of direct foreign investment
will not be repeated this year. However, officials said that
pledged foreign investment is expected to bottom out after 1999.
</P>
